name: Lake Street Single Family Home
description:
Our full-time home (available when we are away), is your perfect place to call "home base" as you explore the city or visit friends.

The space
Great open floor plan home on a quiet tree lined street in one of San Francisco's most coveted neighborhoods. Walking distance to the Presidio, Mountain Lake Park, Laurel Village, Sacramento St shopping and Golden Gate Park. Easy walk to many cafes and restaurants.

The first level features a sunny gourmet kitchen with top-of-the-line appliances, open kitchen/dining area/family area, a lovely foyer, living room with flat panel TV/DirectTV, and a full bathroom with a large whirlpool soaking tub. There is also a small laundry room on this level. There is a deck off kitchen with a Weber grill and the small backyard features a grassy area and patio seating. The second floor has 3 BR's - 1st BR with a Queen Bed, 2nd BR has a full bed and 3rd BR has a twin bed + a twin trundle. A pack-n-play is also available.
host_about: From San Francisco, California.  An active Airbnb Host.

description:
Our home is an absolute jewel box. It is secure, comfortable and decorative. You will never want to leave. It has a working fireplace, chefs kitchen, dedicated parking with Tesla charger (free of charge during off hours) and many more amenities. The neighborhood is quiet, safe and friendly. Our home is not a party house. In respect to our neighbors. Quiet time within reason is appreciated. Ideal for one professional person and or couple, traveling nurses, traveling physician. One month minimum.

The space
Details make this condo stand out from the rest. Stylish interior design, art filled and newly renovated. The condo is on the top floor of a two unit building and has urban city views, located in the desirable & safe Cole Valley Ashbury Heights district near UCSF. Private one car parking with Tesla charger. High end amenities with high thread count linens and towels. Two month minimum preferred but not required.

Bedroom and bathroom
One large bedr
neighborhood_overview: Cole Valley is a small, family-friendly community in the geographical center of the city. Tree-shaded streets are lined with well-kept Victorian homes, and a variety of mom-and-pop shops and relaxed restaurants, including a 1930s-inspired soda fountain. The neighborhood offers hiking at the compact Tank Hill Park, with its panoramic views, or through the dense eucalyptus forest of the Mount Sutro Open Space Reserve.
host_about:
I am an Irish native living in the Desert. My 'Joie de Vivre' is all about entertainment, adventure, travel, the arts in all forms, food and wine (in no particular order) and my home reflects all of this. My wife Jill is an interior designer drawn to atypical, bold, eclectic design yet her works reflect a timeless beauty. Our home is a collaboration of both of our tastes. You will find a kitchen that is compact, efficient & chef clad surrounded by a dining room, living room, two bedrooms and a bathroom that have all been lovingly curated by us both. 
During Covid we both 'worked from home' and were grateful to have this very spacious home in Palm Springs. We managed to integrate it into a magical 'work from home' space offering two dedicated work spaces... one in the master bedroom on a 1960's Paul Puccio pink Onyx desk or additional large L-Shaped work space and the second more formal work desk in another bedroom whereby we custom built a 7' marble desk. The 'work from home' experience is nothing short of perfect with upgraded wifi and Eero ProMesh wifi throughout.

description:

The space
We live in an 1895 Victorian top flat with 12 foot ceilings on the best block in San Francisco. Our calendar is always up to date.

Location Location Location~ Our home is close to the Mission, Lower Haight, and 2.5 blocks from the Castro theater. The underground is 3 blocks away, with a street car even closer. The room is garden-side quiet, and a great price for one of the most expensive neighborhoods in the US!

Please fill out your profile if you are interested~and make sure to arrange a time to meet prior to your arrival, I lead a busy lifestyle, work full time, and wouldn't want to miss anyone! Check in is at 5 and we are 37 steps up from street level.

description:
1920's three bedroom house with a formal dining room, spacious living room and well stocked kitchen. We're located on the southern side of the city, in a quiet, mainly residential neighborhood. Mc Claren Park is a few blocks away as well as bars, banks, bus lines, and the BART is just over a half mile away. One sunny private room with bay windows available on the back side of the house. Its furnished with all the things you'd need including a little desk, dresser and a closet.

The space
Our house is a spacious marina style home, 1,200 square feet. It features a large fully equipped kitchen that you are welcome to use any time. A formal dining room, and big living room with fire place, refurbished oak floors throughout, washer and dryer, wireless hi speed internet, flat screen tv and cable. neighborhood_overview:
2 blocks away is Broken Record. It's a whiskey bar with a kitchen in back. The kitchen has been given some great reviews, delicious southern food.

Also the Dark Horse has a great menu and full bar.

There are a lot of taquerias in the neighborhood, Guadalajara on Mission is my favorite.

Cumaica, Stop and Wrap are our local coffee shops and are within walking distance from the house.

The Mission District and everything it has to offer is the next neighborhood over (2 BART stops, 5 minute drive, 10 minute on bus)
host_about:
Hello! 
My name is Gregory and I moved to San Francisco from Long Beach in my early Twenties. I didn't realize it then, but I would, in time, fall in Love with the Bay Area and never want to move again. 

I have a teenager, triplet sisters, one Basset hound and many nieces and nephews. 

I am a collector of beautiful art and unusual things, I read and write a lot. And enjoy being outdoors with family and friends. Cheep beer, a few hound dogs, meat on the grill, around those I love- pretty much sums up heaven to me.

As a host, I am a wealth of information on this city and surrounding areas, I enjoy people and am open and willing to accommodate your best stay in our vacation rental.

name: Sweet Victorian Charmer with Views
description:
Perched high up on 28th St. with stunning views of downtown and the Bay Bridge from our dining room, living room, kitchen and deck our home can be yours while we're away in December. Parking is free and readily available - no kidding - and public transportation is so close you can see the bus stop from the front door. If you'd like to settle into our little gem after a hard day of sightseeing, let us know!

The space
Our home is more than 100 years old and we love its old world charm. It has lots of wood and lots of windows and an open floor plan so you can enjoy the panoramic view from the kitchen, dining and livingrooms. There is a wrap around deck with plants, a barbeque and a table and chairs - great for breakfast or lunch in good weather. The bedroom has a double bed and we have a double futon mattress that you're welcome to use in the living room. There is one full bathroom.

With garden, deck, and stunning views you might just want to experienc
neighborhood_overview:
We live in a great part of San Francisco. The views are lovely, the air is fresh, the people are friendly, and parking is free and readily available in our part of Noe Valley (as opposed to many other parts of our neighborhood and the city).

We're close to great dining and neighborhood shopping. 24th Street in "downtown" Noe Valley is one of the most delightful neighborhoods in San Francisco. It's like being in a small town in the midst of a big city.

We're also convenient to the "Big City" and to all parts of the Bay Area. We are close to public transportation and to highways that can easily get you to nearby cities and attractions if you have a car. (See "Getting Around" for more details.)
host_about: I'm a Yoga teacher and body movement therapist, happy to share my skills with you for a deeply discounted fee (just give me your tired, your poor). When I'm not doing yoga or helping others feel better I'm often imagining myself in a Latin American country such as Guatemala where I lived with a family and studied Spanish.  If you're up for it, I welcome the opportunity to practice with you.

name: Twin Peaks Home Available for 3+ Month Stays
description:
Our home is located in a quiet, safe neighborhood on the western slope of Twin Peaks. The two upstairs bedrooms are available for rent, on the same floor as the shared kitchen, living & dining rooms and full bath.

We reserve the downstairs bedroom and half bath for ourselves. We spend the majority of the year traveling and working from the road, so chances are that you will have the house to yourself for the majority of your stay.

The space
Our home sits in the geographic center of San Francisco, in a quiet, safe neighborhood with stunning hillside and ocean views. This is an ideal location for those who would rather stay just outside of the active pulse of the inner city. If you have a car, our street has plenty of free parking and no street cleaning, so no parking tickets to worry about.

The house is mid-century, two-levels, with views that look over the hills to the ocean. It has wireless Internet, a 37" HDTV with both Netflix and Amazo
neighborhood_overview:
The neighborhood is quiet and safe and in the geographic center of the city. It's paradise for those who like to walk or run hills.

The walk up to the city's highest point (Twin Peaks) and its 360 degree views takes just 10 minutes. There are numerous hilltop parks and forested trails. Check the book "Stairway Walks in San Francisco". There are many artful stairway walks throughout the city that originate near our house. Cafe's and restaurants are a 20-30 minute walk away in any direction.
host_about:

We're into cooking, music, biking, long walks and hosting gatherings with our friends.

Life is Grand!

description:

Walking distance to close to 100 restaurants, shops, Alamo Cinema Draft House, farmer's market, bars, live music, parks, public transportation and a block and a half from BARTÃ¢â¬Â¦ Sunny, warmest neighborhood in SF, culturally diverse, bursting with life. High Speed Internet, HD TV, Direct TV, HBO/Showtime, Effective 10/1/14, all Airbnb hosts in SF must charge an additional 14% hotel tax on top of room + cleaning per night.

Our newly split level landscaped backyard features a beautiful slate patio, BBQ grill, potted flowers and succulents, mature olive, avocado, apple and pomegranate trees and realistic, artificial turf (SF is really not friendly to grass lawns). neighborhood_overview: The melting pot of cultures, the murals, the restaurants, shops, farmer's market, walkability, festivals, bars, access to BART and MUNI.
host_about:
My wife and I have traveled the world, but have called San Francisco home for 25 years. We invite you to stay with us in our 1896 Edwardian home in the middle of the Mission District, San Francisco's oldest and arguably most vibrant neighborhood filled with a diverse range of some of the City's best restaurants, bars, parks, shops, and more. Not to mention our neighborhood is the warmest, flattest, and fog free part of San Francisco. 

We're 15 minutes from SFO by taxi, a block and a half from the 24th Bart Station and close to many bus and MUNI (subway) lines. Having visited Southeast Asia, Oceania, Australia, Europe, Central America, and of course all over North America, one theme holds true for all our adventures: discover the true culture and flavor wherever we are. 

As your host, we'll do everything we can to make sure you get off the beaten path. We're happy to share our favorite restaurants, local hangouts, and ensure you see the true San Francisco, not just the typical touristy sites. We're into everything from scuba diving, biking, kayaking, hiking, wine, art, music, food, festivals, museums, all things teens, parks, and more. Whatever you're into, we'll point you in the right direction so you have an authentic and memorable time in San Francisco. My motto is from the great Mahatma Ghandi: "Be the change you wish to see in the world." Our style of hosting reflects the needs of our guests. When possible, we like to meet our guests. However we understand that many of them are busy on a tight schedule or not interested to meet us so we respect that. We want to make sure every guest is comfortable and part of that is respecting boundaries and their personal space. 

We look forward to hosting you soon! If you have any questions, please feel free to ask. We're just a click away.

neighborhood_overview: It's The Mission District. a bit gritty but the place to be stationed. Named for Mission Dolores founded in 1776, San FranciscoÃ¢â¬â¢s oldest neighborhood has some of its hottest new restaurants and galleries. Bernal Heights, Potrero Hill These neighborhoods all share a sunny outlook. Boasting some of the best weather in the city, the Mission District, Bernal Heights and Potrero Hill take advantage of an abundance of fog-free days. New restaurants and night spots are a draw while Mission Dolores, 16th and Dolores streets, is the oldest structure in San Francisco. Many of the cityÃ¢â¬â¢s pioneers are buried in an adjacent cemetery. The largest concentration of murals in the city adorn buildings, fences and walls throughout the district. Potrero HillÃ¢â¬â¢s Dogpatch neighborhood is one of 11 historic districts in the city and home to the second crookedest street (after Lombard) in the city.
host_about:
My Motto; "Every Day is a Good Day!"

*As of February 27, 2022  I was fully vaccinated by way of the Pfizer all available vaccine and the two boosters available. I also contracted Covid 19 or a variant in May 2022 and fully recovered.

Something about me and my home; IÃ¢â¬â¢m gay, 64, single, very fit and energetic, very outgoing and easy going. I have always lived in California and have traveled the world extensively. I absolutely love San Francisco and even more being in the Mission District. Entrepreneurial spirited, at age twenty-one I started a business which fulfilled insurersÃ¢â¬â¢ responsibilities for auto losses involving vandalism and retired from that adventure just shy of 36 years later.  I have been vegan for four years now and I have redirected my culinary skills towards all things plant, sugar-free, and fat-free based cuisine.  I enjoy practicing yoga at Love Story just around the corner.  I am also an avid bicyclist and use my bike as my primary mode of transport in the city.  I am attending  Community College SF working my way to a zoological degree. Life is good.

As for my home, the location and views are arguably the best the Mission District can offer. The private roof deck, a green oasis for the otherwise concrete jungle of a Mission Street residence. My place faces west so it's on the street side and is usually quite noisy from people, traffic and sirens. Thankfully the residence was constructed in 2008 and  built  quite soundproof. The bedrooms are well sized and comfortably appointed. The sun always seems to shine in the Mission District.

Finally, I love being an AirBnB host which allows me to share my good fortune, meet wonderful people and make new friends. 

I hope that you choose to stay. 

Mark

host_about:
Andy is a life-long traveler, thrilled to finally be back home in the Bay Area where he grew up and where his extended family still resides.  In 2008 Andy and his wife Tanya were fortunate to find a classic Noe Valley fixer-upper and moved into the cute, tiny Pioneer Victorian where they lived for almost 6 years.  In 2013 they began a complete reconstruction of the 1880's cottage and in 2014 moved their family back into a completely transformed contemporary house equipped for this millenium's lifestyle - the Victorian front remains, but everything behind it now meets the needs and expectations of today (hello, closets and gigabit ethernet...).  Andy has been an at-home Dad since 2000, and has worked in tourism, academia, and as a professional chef.  He loves the vibrant food culture in San Francisco and only wishes he had more time to take advantage of all the amazing arts that San Francisco dishes up on a daily basis as well as the wonderful outdoor spaces, hikes, and bike rides that are nearby.  Andy is very knowledgeable about San Francisco food and fun and is happy to make suggestions to help your stay be enjoyable, fun and tasty, whether you are here for business or family pleasure.

Andy has enjoyed a wide variety of travel styles and accommodations over the years, from $3/night huts on beaches in Eastern Indonesia, simple Ryokan in Japan, and luxury hotels and chateaux in the US, Asia and Europe: the apartment is equipped to closely match the experience of a boutique hotel - luxury finishes throughout and thoughtful amenities - but with a lot more space than most boutique hotels provide!

The "outerlands" as this area of the city used to be called is where nature meets urban, widely and wonderfully. Families, surfers, artists, hipsters, techies and eccentrics come together to create a multicultural neighborhood that is dominated by the ocean and the sky!
Really I think the Sunset District is San Francisco's best kept secret. It is clean and safe and quiet at night. You are about a half hour from the hustle and bustle of downtown (by car or public transport). Out here the streets are wider, the backyards bigger, and free parking is easy to find. People who like the outdoors love the location, especially for surfing, jogging, cycling, and hiking.
Typically the Sunset can be foggy in June and July, but is clear and beautiful most of the rest of the year. Fall is stellar. Yearly temperatures hover in the 60-65 degrees. 'Not all who wander are lost.' I love this quote.

After retiring from a full time teaching career I have provided regular,  part time child care for my adorable grandkids, taken lots of art classes and traveled. We attend the opera and I attend the ballet. I love museums and I am a member of most of those in the city. In addition both of us and our family members are long time devoted SF Giants fans!

name: Classic Elegance Pacific Heights
description:
This grand 1908 home is the epitome of sophistication, close to The Presidio, Fillmore, and Laurel Village shops and restaurants. It is filled with classic details and luxury amenities, two gardens, and fabulous cooking and entertaining spaces. It is ideal for corporate team-building, adult family gatherings, and deluxe getaways with friends.

The space
This is an historic 1908 home in the Mediterranean style, designed by Carl Mueseldorffer, a noted SF architect. It was the home of Senator Dianne Feinstein when she was Mayor of San Francisco, and was featured in Architectural Digest when it was owned by noted interior designer Suzanne Tucker. It is made of wood, smoking, vaping, and candles are not allowed in the house! Rooms have high ceilings and lovely molding and detailing. It is filled with books, which you are welcome to peruse. It is designed to be warm and inviting, but still refined. We hope you enjoy the space as much as we have.

When the hous
neighborhood_overview:
Pacific Heights offers the best of San Francisco living. The Presidio is just a few blocks away -- go to the Starbuck's next to Lucasfilm and see the Yoda statue in front of the building. On Sundays there is an "Off the Grid" food truck gathering from 11-3 -- a great way to sample a number of specialties. Then walk it off along Crissy Field beach, with incomparable views of the Golden Gate Bridge and Alcatraz.
If you amble down Sacramento Street to the right you will reach charming Laurel Village, with upscale family shops, restaurants, and services. If you walk left you will come to Divisadero -- don't miss B Patisserie on California just before Divisadero -- pastries to die for, and lovely sandwiches across the street at B on the Go. Keep going four more blocks and you'll be on tony Fillmore Street, home to some of the chicest shops in SF. Great upscale Indian food at Dosa, Italian at SPQR and Pizzeria Delfina, and liquid nitrogen ice cream at Smitten. Stroll Union Street for
host_about:
I am a writer with far-flung interests and a penchant for people. I am the author of books and articles on style, art and travel. I also write corporate financial reports and marketing materials, which reflects my previous career managing a service-oriented healthcare business for seniors. I also serve as a board member of nonprofit organizations; the fabric of our communities is much stronger when everyone has an opportunity to succeed. 

I love to make people comfortable; this home reflects that, along with a desire for functionality, luxury and beauty. I am fortunate to live in one of the most magical places in the world. Sharing this home ensures that more people are able to appreciate this vibrant, diverse, and delightful City by the Bay.

host_about:
Hi, I'm Ben. I started using Airbnb when traveling in 2012 and have not booked a hotel room since. Some of my all-time favorite trips include New York, Miami, Tokyo and Sydney (especially Sydney!). In my opinion, immersing yourself into the neighborhoods, cultures and people of the city you're visiting is superior in every way to staying in some sterile hotel. 

I am a native San Franciscan and I recently I started listing a room in my own San Francisco apartment on Airbnb. I would love to share my knowledge of the fantastic sights, food and art scenes that San Francisco has to offer to the right travelers.

"A journey is best measured in friends, not in miles". - Tim Cahill

host_about:
I manage the house with Lita my 21 year old daughter & her father Fred. Having our house on Airbnb is helping us with our daughters college fund. She graduated from High School in 2019 & has taken a gap & COVID year before deciding on a university & country that she wants to go to school in. 

Renting our home also funded a new garden apartment that will be for a long term tenant.

Airbnb also helped fund 'Tartlet Bar',  a food business Wendy had with her families farm.

We own the house together, but split our time there with Lita our daughter. We co-parent & raised our daughter in whatÃ¢â¬â¢s called a Ã¢â¬ÅnestingÃ¢â¬Â situation. One of us are usually in town & available if you need anything.

We have lived in San Francisco since 1989, we get out of the city as much as possible, but always seem to return.

Wendy is a creative consultant & avid paddle boarder. She speaks French, English, understands Spanish & is learning Portuguese. She's currently a digital nomad making her way around the continents. One of her passions is to see the world and study different cultures, which she has done extensively (she wants to be an anthropologist when she grows up ;.). 

We believe the world is Lita's education, with 3 languages and several countries already under her belt she is a gypsy at heart. SheÃ¢â¬â¢s fluent in French, Spanish, English, & is teaching herself Japanese. She took 2019/2020 to explore Europe & work in Japan before she attends a University in 2022.

Fred is French, fluent in French, English & Spanish, a photographer, entrepreneur, surfer, world traveler and owns two small business in SF; Dalva (a bar in the mission district) and Grenouille-French Vintage Antiques.

We're also doing Airbnb because we like the idea of meeting like minded travelers, people who seek adventure, people who believe we can learn from everyone we meet and enjoy absorbing other cultures as much as we do. Is it possible to be part of a community while being a gypsy and a nomad? So far it's working out to be yes...

neighborhood_overview:
Bernal Heights is a very safe residential neighborhood in San Francisco. It's super quiet and peaceful at night. Because it's on a hill, it has the feel of a small village in the heart of the city. It's very charming!

Bernal Heights features good parks, lots of popular restaurants, and some of the best panoramic views of the city. We are two short blocks away from the main street Cortland Ave., which has a unique small village feel to it, even though it's full of trendy restaurants and cafes.

On Cortland Ave. you will find just about anything you need. There are three cafes, three bars, a gym, a grocery store, Bank of America, a meat market, wine bar, art gallery, a plant store (succulents), a public library, food vendors, a pet store, and a small-batch artisanal goods store.

There are two great parks and a Recreation Center with a basketball court.

The restaurants are plentiful. San Francisco is a foodie town after all. On Cortland Ave. yo

host_about:
ABOUT ME
I grew up in Cleveland, Ohio, and became an exchange student in South Africa at the age of 16. Living abroad changed my life forever. I have since gone back to live in South Africa a second time. 

While traveling, I met amazing people including a Parisian woman, on a train, who invited me to visit her in Paris. When I arrived, she gave me the keys to her apartment and said I could stay as long as IÃ¢â¬â¢d like. From that moment on, I made a vow to help as many travelers as possible on their journeys. That is why AIRBNB appeals to me - the art of travel, connection, culture, and sharing the City I love with others. 

INTERESTS
Nature. Spiritual pursuits. Traditional Japanese culture. The art of Tea. Gardening. Enjoying animals and taking care of backyard wildlife. Exploring San Francisco. Exercise, inline skating. Reading/listening to books are my constant companions.

I am a passionate learner and love languages.  I have dabbled in English, Spanish, Afrikaans, Indo-Malay & Arabic. 

COUNTRIES IÃ¢â¬â¢VE VISITED
Japan, Peru, South Africa, Malaysia, Thailand, Switzerland, France, Belgium, & Italy.

FAMILY
My husband, Raul, is a native Peruvian who speaks excellent Spanish, loves to cook, and enjoys all types of cuisine.  He is a passionate Architect and Design Professional.  Raul is also an Artist when he can make the time.  

My Mom, Gerry, makes guest appearances.  She lives on the ground floor and is active with friends, exercising, museums, and is an avid quilter.  Like me, she is formerly from Ohio and was an active skier and sailor back in the day.  She, too, is a world traveler.

HOSTING
As a Host, I enjoy nurturing Guests and making sure they feel well cared for and even spoiled. My Guests enjoy my many versions of Ã¢â¬ÅteaÃ¢â¬Â and baked goodies, as well as wicked bowls of popcorn! 

I have always been complimented on my eye for detail and desire to make even the ordinary feel special. 

From the lovely view, peaceful setting, and friendly outdoor animal visitors, to the manner in which I go out of my way to make things unique and fulfill requests, you can count on having a positive stay and look forward to a return visit to our beloved home on the hill in exciting San Francisco.

host_about: I have lived in San Francisco since 2003 on and off; originally hailing from Ohio. I don't smoke, won't bring along a pet and leave places just as clean as I found them. Airbnb has been a great way to keep us traveling while providing the right comfort level for a small family.  Excited to be able to host visitors to SF by sharing my space and some of my favorite recommendations.

neighborhood_overview:
This neighborhood is the Sunset/Parkside District, which is on the western side of San Francisco. There is easy access to many amenities and to public transportation. The streetcar stop is one block away. The streetcar (L Taraval line) will get you downtown in about 20 minutes. If you have a car, parking is free but can get tricky in the evenings. (Sometimes we can save spots for our guests.) The freeways are close also, if you need them. We are within a couple miles of wonderful parts of San Francisco, including Ocean Beach, Stern Grove, LandÃ¢â¬â¢s End and Golden Gate Park. There are bars and restaurants within easy walking distance. There is also a laundromat and a 24 hour convenience store on the corner. This is a very safe neighborhood.

We have lived in this house for 40 years. Some neighbors on our block have been here even longer, which is highly unique in San Francisco.

We love to walk to the beach (slightly over a mile) and watch the sun set.
host_about:
Hi there.  We have been married and living in this house that we love for 40 years.  Our daughter attended school in the neighborhood, and our next door neighbors on both sides have lived here even longer than we have. 

I moved to San Francisco in 1977; Charlie arrived in the 1960s. We still believe this is the best city in the world, despite its many difficult changes.

I am an outdoor person!  I roller skate all over town, and lead the weekly (world famous) San Francisco Friday Night Skate.  Charlie is an indoor person.  One of his favorite things to do is cook, and he's fabulous at it.

Thanks for reading!

name: Private Loft and Free Parking in Charming SF Home
description:
An Edwardian-style house, built in 1910, with private cozy loft that includes a bedroom with queen bed, skylight, spacious bathroom, dormer window with sweeping views, TV, Wi-Fi, and kitchenette space. All located just minutes away from Hwy 280, BART, City College main campus, Stonestown Galleria and Ocean Ave restaurants.

The space
Guests will access the loft through the front door, where stairs will lead them directly upstairs to their cozy loft. The home is located on hill with beautiful views of Twin Peaks, Mount Davidson, Sutro Tower, and the East Bay. Whole Foods, coffee shops, yoga studios, restaurants, bars, SF City College, and several public-transportation options are all within short walking distance. During the COVID-19 pandemic we provide a "no-contact stay" policy to help protect our guests. Our check-in and check-out protocol will be provided the week of guest arrival.

Guest access
In addition to the loft, guests are welcome
neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood is a diverse mix of long-time family residents and young, newer homeowners, mostly from the tech industry. The Mission district is two stops away on the BART. The downtown Powell St. cable car (which will take you to Fisherman's Wharf) is just 15 minutes on the BART. Attractions near the home include the Ocean Ave. shopping district, Ocean Beach, the SF Zoo, Stern Grove, and West Portal, among many others.
host_about:
Hello. I'm Spencer. Five things I can't live without include my family, reading history books, my church community, good barbecue, and gardening in my backyard. Some of my favorite travel destinations are Monterey for the beautiful aquarium, Texas to see my sisters and brother, and Sonoma, just across the Golden Gate Bridge. I enjoy classic jazz, gospel, the blues, and theater, as well as soul food, and baking.

As a host, I'm happy to provide sightseeing recommendations and friendly travel advice. All guests, regardless of their race or background, will be treated with respect, and we expect the same treatment from them during their stay in our home. Interaction beyond what is required during check-in and checkout, is optional. Privacy and property is also to be respected.  

Traveling is a wonderful way to meet new people and learn about different cultures. I hope you enjoy your destination wherever you decide to stay.

neighborhood_overview:
Potrero Hill is the sunniest and warmest neighborhood in San Francisco. We rarely get the famous San Francisco fog, even on days when we can see the fog roll in over downtown from our living room.

We have many popular restaurants on 18th Street within walking distance from our home. Chez Maman (French), Mochica (Peruvian), Umi (Japanese), and others. As well as Farley's for your morning coffee, or Blooms for your evening martini and a game of pool.

description:

HACKNSLEEP,COM

The space

neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood is called Nob Hill. YouÃ¢â¬â¢ll be right around the corner from shops, coffee houses, restaurants, bars on Polk street, and grocery stores including Trader JoeÃ¢â¬â¢s and Whole Foods. Take a jog down to China town, or a walk over to FishermanÃ¢â¬â¢s Wharf. A 15 minute bike ride puts you right in the Financial District for an easy commute to and from work. host_about:
Welcome to Bed|n|Build! Bed|n|Build provides a landing pad for entrepreneurs, designers, coders, engineers and other innovators and builders from the broader startup community.

When staying with us, you'll meet like-minded individuals with a culture of pragmatic cooperation and collaboration. We are more than just about housing. We care, build trusted relationships, and support each other in achieving our goals and startup visions. 

We offer private and shared bedrooms that allow even bootstrapping founders to live in a great neighborhood and the friendly, clean, convenient, and safe place they deserve. 

We partner with startup accelerators, bootcamps, coding academies, and co-working spaces and prefer recruiting our residents through peer-recommendations and our networks. So please let us know how you have heard from us.

I am also an entrepreneur and builder who now runs an international startup accelerator out of Palo Alto, SF, and NYC. When I bring founders from abroad, one of the hardest challenges for them is to find appropriate housing. That's why I stepped up and created Bed|n|Build.

We love social, easy going, and low maintenance folks. After all, it's a co-living place with diverse people from the different corners of this world. Nerdy - sure. Geeky - also welcome. 

Don't reach out if others have described you as picky, high maintenance, or a drama king or queen. Also, do not contact us if you are not interested in getting to know the other builders sharing the house or joining the Happy Hours that we organize for the community occasionally.

There is a delicate European flair to many of the boutiques and restaurants found along the lushly green streets of Jackson, Union, and Hyde. Green and Polk Streets offer exceptional international cuisine from French to Italian to Vietnamese, you can't go wrong in this vibrant stretch of city. If shopping is on your list, don't miss the many delightful boutiques dotting Polk Street between Union and Broadway.

host_about:
We may be new to AirBnB but we have been renting our San Francisco home to guests for over 15 years and have rented many places away from home for our travels over the years. We are careful and considerate non-smoking guests who take good care of the places we stay and are looking for guests to stay in our home who will do the same. 

We have over 200 5 star reviews on our other platforms (VR/HA/TA) so you can rent with confidence that you will have a great place to stay aided by thoughtful, helpful and experienced hosts.

We are a retirement age couple who find ourselves away from San Francisco often these days. Although we love our home and we love San Francisco, we also like to travel. Now we rent our home to guests like you while we are away. When we are home we are usually working to upgrade and refresh our house. We know you will enjoy the results!

We have lived in the San Francisco area for almost 50 years and purchased our San Francisco home in 1999. In 2004 we began to spend time away and a friend suggested we offer it to guests on vacation or in San Francisco on business. We soon learned that people really enjoyed our home-like atmosphere. We are thrilled with the response we have gotten and we work hard to keep our new and returning guests contented and feeling cared for. Visitors say they appreciate our clean and well appointed home and our knowledge of the city and professional attitude.

Most guests mention the feeling of a being in a real home as soon as they enter. We think this is because we still live there part of each year and keep the house comfortable and well maintained not only for our guests but for ourselves as well. We are also proud of our garden, keeping it maintained even while we are away. We paint, scrape, clean, renew, update and replace parts of the house every time we come to visit. We think it shows. 

Our guests certainly enjoy our home. Read the reviews! 170 Five Star ratings on HA/VR and 75 on TA. We get these ratings not because everything is always perfect (we do try, however!) but because we go out of our way to help our guests settle in and feel at home and we respond quickly to any question. Finally, if you are bringing a car, you will absolutely love our little garage (for economy to mid-size cars). Parking rules in SF can make you dizzy. If you don't bring a car - great! - hop on the bus one block from the front door and head downtown or to the beach.

You can read more about our home at YourHomeInSanFrancisco. 
Thanks!

neighborhood_overview:
This neighborhood is undeniably one of the best in San Francisco. It's quiet, safe, and peaceful, and has the most charming main street (24th Street) of all the neighborhoods in San Francisco.

And it's just a stone's throw away from the entertainment in the adjacent Castro and the Mission neighborhoods. Uber and Lyft are everywhere and wait times are generally less than 5 min for a pick up.

Also nearby:

- Cute neighborhood feeling Whole Foods is a 15 min walk
- Several tech shuttle bus stops are a 15 min walk

host_about:
Born in Shanghai, raised in Virginia Beach, worked in Singapore for 6 years, and now based in San Fran (yeah I said it).

Traveling and eating my way through the world are my ultimate passions!  That's one of the reasons why I decided to work for a company where I can inspire travelers to explore this great wide world of ours and experience it like a local!

I like the big cities for their diversity in people, energetic airports and mass transit, unique architecture, rooftop vista points, cafe culture, and how could I forget the variety of nomz.  I don't care much for main street shopping or gridlock traffic.

I equally like the unbeaten path for the sense of adventure, learning the local way of life, being able to see more than 10 stars at night, and loving the fact that I'm a little blue dot in the middle of nowhere on G00gle maps.  I'm not a fan of mozzies or sunblock eye sting.

Besides traveling and eating the world, I keep an active lifestyle of hitting the gym and playing tennis and volleyball.  But please don't ask me to do any distance running.  

I live by the golden rule of mutual respect, and I also appreciate tidiness.  Your home is in good hands with me.  Smoke? No. Drink? Not so much.  Ohm nom nom? Oh hell yeah!!

:-) :-)

neighborhood_overview:
The Mission is San Francisco's hippest neighborhood, full of restaurants, shops, music and art venues, street art and everything else you might want in an urban environment. Grocery stores, vegetable, fruit, seafood and meat markets begin within 2 blocks. Eclectic bars, restaurants and cafes in every direction. The subway (BART) and 5 bus lines converge 2 blocks away. Pre Covid, the Mission was home to the city's best bakeries, best organic supermarket, best coffee roasters, best dining and destination after hour bars.
Even today, you'll find street murals, independent bookstores, Latin vibe, Carnaval, Galeria de la Raza, Dolores Park, Dia de los Muertos, roving mariachis, The Roxie Theater, thrift stores, Victorian homes, hipsters and homeboys, quirky bars and the best weather in the City. I love my neighborhood!
host_about: My name is Michael.  I'm originally from New York City, and I was a long term resident of San Francisco.  I also lived for many years in Mexico, and  I  currently live in Bahia, Brazil. I speak Spanish and Portuguese fluently.   I've been an Airbnb guest on five continents, and I was also an Airbnb host in my home in San Francisco's Mission District.  My passions are books, travel, and languages.

host_about:
'Not all who wander are lost.' I love this quote. 
I am that wanderer, incredibly lucky to be infected with the passion and audacity to travel often and solo. 
I was born and raised in San Francisco. I am a native. I love my city. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve watched it evolve. But I have also left it many times in my youth. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left it to study abroad in France. Best decision of my college life! I backpacked solo around western Europe. 
IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left SF when I was in the military and stationed around our country. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve also driven as far north as Niagara Falls.
Career wise, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve spent over a decade in property management and rentals. I'm also a realtor. As a hobby, I write as often as possible, a pen and notebook on me at all times.
I am cursed with this blessing of being unceasingly interested in people. I love meeting people. I love hearing stories. And I love writing them. 
As I review my lifeÃ¢â¬â¢s experiences, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve come upon one very simple realization, that proclaimed secret of success. It is merely this: Ã¢â¬ËSay what you will do and do what you will say.Ã¢â¬â¢
The prolific Seth Godin, talented blogger said creativity isnÃ¢â¬â¢t the most important part. What counts is being able to ship! Ship on time. And ship again. And again. And again.

Near restaurants, bars, and boutiques of Chestnut Street. Easy (and flat!) walk to many attractions, including the Palace of Fine Arts, the Presidio, Fort Mason, Fisherman's Wharf, Crissy Field and the beach. Perfect launchpad to explore it all.

Price includes cleaning with change of linens monthly.

The space
ABOUT THE HOME
The flat has been freshly renovated with marble baths, designer furniture, linen window treatments, wool carpets and dark hardwoods. At 1700 sq. feet, it's spacious and light-filled, with large bedrooms and comfy furniture. Bedrooms are separated down the hallway from living, dining and cooking spaces. neighborhood_overview: The Marina is a picturesque San Francisco neighborhood sitting right on the Bay, equi-walking distance from urban and natural attractions. Boutique shopping, bars and restaurants are a couple blocks away on both Chestnut and Union streets. Walk to grocery stores, bookshops, ice cream parlors, the library and movie theaters. The Marina Green is a half block up the street, and from there folks get a stunning view of the San Francisco Bay, from the Golden Gate Bridge through Alcatraz. It's a short walk to the beach. Turn east and head to Fort Mason, Fisherman's Wharf and onto the Embarcadero. Turn west to The Palace of Fine Arts, Crissy Field, the Presidio, and right over the Golden Gate Bridge. Access to Wine Country couldn't be simplerÃ¢â¬âjust head over the Golden Gate Bridge and explore.
host_about:
I love San Francisco and am happy you're here!  I'm a design geek, foodie, scuba diver, and podcast host. I keep an eye on SFJazz and the latest at SFMOMA and the DeYoung. Dim sum is my weakness. I've got lots of city favorites and they're all in my house binder. (Spoiler alerts: Ice Cream Bar, Namu Gaji, A16, Bi-Rite, Calistoga mud baths, Fanny the Supermutt and taking the hills by Vespa!) I love stepping outside to the Golden Gate Bridge, the Bay and a gourmet Dynamo Donut. 

I'm happy to help you have a fun and relaxing stay here by the Bay!

Plenty of closet and dresser space.
neighborhood_overview: Named for Mission Dolores founded in 1776, San FranciscoÃ¢â¬â¢s oldest neighborhood has some of its hottest new restaurants and galleries.  It has the best weather in the city.  For those who are looking to explore the true heart of the Mission District with its artistic depth, nightlife, and vibrant cuisines, this is the place for you. You are sure to find hidden lounges, evolving mural art,  top rated restaurants and a true San Francisco experience such as urban putting, rock climbing gym, a movie theater serving drinks and food a block away.  You can also  walk to both the fun hip Dolores Park and the famous Castro neighborhood, both of which are additionally must-sees during any San Francisco stay.

host_about:
Welcome to HacknSleep! Hacknsleep provides a landing pad for entrepreneurs, designers, coders, engineers and other innovators and builders from the broader startup community.

When staying with us, you'll meet like-minded individuals with a culture of pragmatic cooperation and collaboration. We are more than just about housing. We care, build trusted relationships, and support each other in achieving our goals and startup visions. 

We offer private and shared bedrooms that allow even bootstrapping founders to live in a great neighborhood and the friendly, clean, convenient, and safe place they deserve. 

We partner with startup accelerators, bootcamps, coding academies, and co-working spaces and prefer recruiting our residents through peer-recommendations and our networks. So please let us know how you have heard from us.

I am also an entrepreneur and builder who now runs an international startup accelerator out of Palo Alto, SF, and NYC. When I bring founders from abroad, one of the hardest challenges for them is to find appropriate housing. That's why I stepped up and created Bed|n|Build.

We love social, easy going, and low maintenance folks. After all, it's a co-living place with diverse people from the different corners of this world. Nerdy - sure. Geeky - also welcome. 

Don't reach out if others have described you as picky, high maintenance, or a drama king or queen. Also, do not contact us if you are not interested in getting to know the other builders sharing the house or joining the Happy Hours that we organize for the community occasionally.

neighborhood_overview:
Historical Telegraph Hill ( VERY SAFE AREA)
Now: The iconic Coit Tower is the focal point of the area for most visitors, but if you're willing to take your time and wander (and hike a couple of steep stretches of steps) you can catch a lot of extra scenery. Many people take the Greenwich Street steps since they are closest to the tower, and return the same way. The Filbert Street steps, just to the south, lead through much more of the lush landscaping characteristic of Telegraph Hill. Our neighborhood is also known for supporting a flock of feral parrots, primarily red-masked parakeets (Aratinga erythrogenys), descended from escaped or released pets. The flock was popularized by a book and subsequent documentary (2003), both titled The Wild Parrots of Telegraph Hill.

Then: The name Telegraph Hill came from a structure built on the top of the hill in the mid-1800s, which would visually signal the city with regard to the type of vessels passing through the Golden Gate.
host_about:
Greetings!
Thank you for viewing my profile! We are self employed and also philanthropists residing in San Francisco. My husband and I are high school sweet hearts with four wonderful children!   We love traveling and think of NYC as our second city, being that we visit at least 3 - 4 times a year for 20 years.

Exploring the world to learn about other people and cultures is our passion. We enjoy meeting new friends globally !  When we are at home we love entertaining others, getting together with family, spearheading or volunteering  a community service endeavor, going out to dance for exercise, or attending the local performing arts and theaters. 

My husband and I enjoyed Airbnb a few times during our travels. Wow, great experience! We like Airbnb homes as they offer more space, comfort and opportunities for us to live amongst the locals! What fun! We recently decided to host guests during their visit in hopes to enhance their experience and provide opportunities to discover new friends and explore our beautiful city with a unit close to all attractions!

FAVORITES: 
TRAVEL DESTINATIONS - Rome, Paris, Venice, Shanghai, New York, and England!
BOOKS - Anything suspenseful or historical
SHOWS - Mama Mia, Phantom of the Opera, Jersey Boys
MOVIES - True Lies, Harry Potter, anything James Bond, Sweet Home Alabama
MUSIC - Artists: Coldplay, Maroon 5, John Mayer, and Madonna / Classic Orchestra  Pieces / and Pop
FOOD - This is a hard one because I love to eat everything, especially fusion and innovative! creations!
CANNOT LIVE WITHOUT: My family, participating in community service to help others, my stove, traveling, and going to great restaurants!
MOTTO: Kindness is the language which the deaf can hear and the blind can see.
Mark Twain

Wishing all the best for Happy Trails! 
Sharon

host_about:
I run the high-end hospitality management company called Standout Stays.

I'm from South Africa and lived in Tokyo, Japan before moving to San Francisco over 25 years ago. I gave up my Business Development career in 2016 to focus full-time on short-term rentals. 

I have traveled to 50+ countries and stayed at some amazing places. I know what a difference great hospitality can make. I thus strive to create an experience at Standout Stays that will be memorable and unique. My aim is that you will come back and stay at our properties again each time you are back in the area.   

As a guest, I am responsible, trustworthy, and neat. Being a host myself, I can completely put myself in your shoes and am very respectful of your space. I love AirBNB because it affords one the opportunity to live like a local when you travel to a new area.  

I enjoy spending time with my dog (Dexter), working out, hiking, skiing, and generally making the most of life.   

If you are considering booking one of our listings, I know you will love your stay!  And for more information about our company, just search for us.

Hope to meet you soon,  
Laurence

IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left SF when I was in the military and stationed around our country. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve also driven as far north as Niagara Falls.
Career wise, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve spent over a decade in property management and rentals. I'm also a realtor. As a hobby, I write as often as possible, a pen and notebook on me at all times.
I am cursed with this blessing of being unceasingly interested in people. I love meeting people. I love hearing stories. And I love writing them. 
As I review my lifeÃ¢â¬â¢s experiences, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve come upon one very simple realization, that proclaimed secret of success. It is merely this: Ã¢â¬ËSay what you will do and do what you will say.Ã¢â¬â¢

neighborhood_overview:
Potrero Hill has some of the best views in San Francisco as well as weather. It's a quiet neighborhood, with mostly single-family homes and PARKING! Finding parking in San Francisco can be challenging and expensive, but not an issue on Potrero Hill which makes it a parking gem that's conveniently located. Its location makes it ideal for fun walks to all of the eastern parts of San Francisco where a good portion of the places one would like to visit are located; AT&T Park, Ferry Building and Market, Exploratorium, Coit Tower, Chinatown, Northbeach, Fisherman's Wharf and Alcatraz. Not to mention, one can take a gorgeous ferry ride over to Sausalito and Tiburon from the Ferry Building.
Downtown, Financial District and Moscone Center are about a 30 minute walk from Potrero Hill. Of course one can Uber or Lyft to these locations as well.

neighborhood_overview:
The Potrero Hill district is one of the most unique neighborhoods in San Francisco and has gone through several changes from working class to the newer family oriented direction since the 1990's

Potrero Hill is one of the sunniest neighborhoods in San Francisco. It is insulated from our famous fog and chill from the ocean and gives some of the most spectacular views of downtown and the bay bridge. If you are up for a few hills it can be a great walking experience and the ever growing "hub" of 18th street is always a great place to start a day.

One of the best parts of Potrero Hill is that it is a neighborhood further from the "hustle and bustle" so it has a quiet and sleepy feel but you are never more than a few minutes from the fray.
host_about:
We are working professionals whom love this city and takes a lot of pride in showing people how great a place it is.  We love world traveling, enjoying other cultures and meeting new people.

We are big movie buffs, foodies to our core and can't live without some good coffee :) 

Giving new people an opportunity to experience San Francisco is what we hope to do as hosts.  One of us was born in San Francisco (the other in Miami) and think there are a ton of fantastic things to experience here while on your stay either for work or fun :)

We hope that people have a fun and relaxing stay but mostly are happy!

host_about:
I run the high-end hospitality management company called Standout Stays.

I'm from South Africa and lived in Tokyo, Japan before moving to San Francisco over 25 years ago. I gave up my Business Development career in 2016 to focus full-time on short-term rentals. 

I have traveled to 50+ countries and stayed at some amazing places. I know what a difference great hospitality can make. I thus strive to create an experience at Standout Stays that will be memorable and unique. My aim is that you will come back and stay at our properties again each time you are back in the area.   

As a guest, I am responsible, trustworthy, and neat. Being a host myself, I can completely put myself in your shoes and am very respectful of your space. I love AirBNB because it affords one the opportunity to live like a local when you travel to a new area.  

I enjoy spending time with my dog (Dexter), working out, hiking, skiing, and generally making the most of life.

Laurence

host_about:
I love to travel and fell in love with San Francisco on a trip and just had to move here!  I'm so happy and proud to be a San Franciscan!  I love sharing the city's beautiful landscape, neighborhoods and culture with first-time visitors and long-term residents alike.  

My family and I own several apartments that we have restored with love and care.  Our furnished apartments are always rented out long-term.  When we have a short gap between renters, we occasionally are able to offer a unit on Airbnb.  Sometimes, it's even a way to find great tenants--especially for those that like to "try before they buy."  

There are lots of great and useful ways to use Airbnb to help San Francisco's new, existing and future residents.  My goal is to insure guests have an excellent and authentic SF experience, and that they discover a few reasons that they might want to call SF home!

host_about:
I manage the house with Lita my 21 year old daughter & her father Fred. Having our house on Airbnb is helping us with our daughters college fund. She graduated from High School in 2019 & has taken a gap & COVID year before deciding on a university & country that she wants to go to school in. 

Renting our home also funded a new garden apartment that will be for a long term tenant.

Airbnb also helped fund 'Tartlet Bar',  a food business Wendy had with her families farm.

We own the house together, but split our time there with Lita our daughter. We co-parent & raised our daughter in whatÃ¢â¬â¢s called a Ã¢â¬ÅnestingÃ¢â¬Â situation. One of us are usually in town & available if you need anything.

We have lived in San Francisco since 1989, we get out of the city as much as possible, but always seem to return.

Wendy is a creative consultant & avid paddle boarder. She speaks French, English, understands Spanish & is learning Portuguese. She's currently a digital nomad making her way around the continents. One of her passions is to see the world and study different cultures, which she has done extensively (she wants to be an anthropologist when she grows up ;.). 

We believe the world is Lita's education, with 3 languages and several countries already under her belt she is a gypsy at heart. SheÃ¢â¬â¢s fluent in French, Spanish, English, & is teaching herself Japanese. She took 2019/2020 to explore Europe & work in Japan before she attends a University in 2022.

Fred is French, fluent in French, English & Spanish, a photographer, entrepreneur, surfer, world traveler and owns two small business in SF; Dalva (a bar in the mission district) and Grenouille-French Vintage Antiques.

We're also doing Airbnb because we like the idea of meeting like minded travelers, people who seek adventure, people who believe we can learn from everyone we meet and enjoy absorbing other cultures as much as we do. Is it possible to be part of a community while being a gypsy and a nomad? So far it's working out to be yes...

There is a Safeway and laundromat within walking distance (~6 minutes), as well as numerous excellent restaurants on Clement and Geary streets. We will be happy to discuss with you our favorites and they will be noted in the apartment information materials. It's a great location to enjoy the city and only a short 5-7 minute drive to the Golden Gate Bridge. If you have a car, it's easy to visit Sausalito, the Marin Headlands or head up for a day of wine tasting in Napa or Sonoma.
host_about:

I'm a bit of an exercise fanatic and am happy to help with urban and not so urban hiking itineraries that are sure to please and that are  easily accessible from our home.  FYI - My husband is fluent in French and Portuguese and is passable in Spanish and Italian. 
Lastly, we are well traveled and hope that  your stay with us will be as enjoyable an AirB&B experience as we have had  ourselves!

Yusuke, Michael, Carmina and Sharon.

I am from the Mediterranean area and have been an artist all my life . I am an interior designer and a real estate agent working with Keller Williams. 
I am professional, hospitable, very quiet, non smoker, extremely clean, open minded, athletic, social, interested in the arts, real estate and business.
I love nature and outdoor activities. I snow ski, swim, hike, bike, dance, cook, draw and paint. I enjoy watching movies such as: Like Water for Chocolate, Chocolat, Les Intouchables, Gladiator, Braveheart, The Lion King, ET, Avatar, Pretty Woman, Shawshanck Redemption, The last of the Mohicans, Pride & Prejudice, the history channels, documentaries, etc... 
I am sociable, outgoing, hospitable, love good conversation and great food. I traveled extensively around the world and lived abroad. Since my teens, I try each year, to discover one or 2 new cities or countries. I enjoy learning and discovering new cultures as I appreciate people and the world.
Some of the main countries I have visited in Europe, South America, Central and North America including the Arab World are:
 France, England, Italy, Germany, Austria, Sweden , Denmark, Portugal, Spain, Basque, Greece, Cypress, Turkey,  Lebanon, Jordan, Syria, United Arab Emirates, Israel, Morocco and the Sahara desert. 
I also traveled throughout the Caribbean, Central America and visited Peru, Ecuador and Indonesia. 
It is my pleasure to welcome you to my home and make it: "Your Home away from Home"

host_about:
Your comfort is my first priority.  I provide quality furnishings and give you privacy.  I try to make sure you have everything you might need and am available to make recommendations about SF for you, or take care of any maintenance. 

My rentals are extremely well cleaned. The house is being extremely well ventilated, as it's on the top of a hill where it's breezy and sunny. We open every single closet, cabinet, and drawer and inspect them and let them ventilate.

All non-porous surfaces are cleaned with soap, ammonia, or bleach.  All fabric surfaces are either vacuumed or washed with a soapy cloth.  All linens and towels are washed with bleach in hot water.. 

The cleaners and I wear masks during cleaning. We use trash bags to avoid contact with trash and simplify cleaning the trash cans.  We try to run two loads of dishes between guests, so you may find a load running when you arrive. 

You can see the cleaning guidelines weÃ¢â¬â¢re following here:
 https://www.airbnb.com/resources/hosting-homes/a/cleaning-guidelines-to-help-prevent-the-spread-of-covid-19-163

neighborhood_overview:
Our Miraloma Park neighborhood has the best of both worlds. We have a beautiful view of Twin Peaks. Mt Davidson (the highest mountain in San Francisco), Twin Peaks, and Glen Canyon Park trails are available for trekkers. We are also 2 blocks away from commerce including Starbucks, Mollie's Stone Supermarket, CVS Pharmacy, family-owned bakery and restaurants. Most homes in this neighborhood are single family homes.
We are located near West Portal where there are many good local and diverse restaurants, as well as boutique stores, and a movie theater.

description:
Your guests will love you for bringing them to this private, quiet, comfy, modern guest suite. Located in a quiet neighborhood, yet just minutes to everywhere you'll want to go. Spacious bedrooms with king beds. Huge living/dining area. Fully equipped kitchen. Balcony decks with romantic views. Two TVs. Quality furnishings. Immaculately clean. Easy parking. The space
Enjoy this 100% private, spacious, upstairs guest suite in a quiet, residential neighborhood. You get 1,500 sq ft (140 sq. m) of space. Everything has been recently upgraded.

Your friends and family will love being in the big, sunny, airy living room with views of the San Francisco Bay and Silicon Valley, high ceiling, fireplace, 55" TV, and large view deck. Modern kitchen & BBQ. Relax in the deep tub. Have sweet dreams in the huge King and Cal King beds.
neighborhood_overview:
This safe, quiet neighborhood in the hills of SF is a short walk from McLaren Park where you can enjoy a hike or long run, find a natural spring, and take in views of the Bay Area.

This location is quiet and private, but it's about a 1 mile walk to restaurants, so usually you'll start your adventures with a short car ride. San Francisco is a small city, and you can go anywhere in a few minutes by car, traffic permitting. You can drive to the Golden Gate Bridge in as little as 20 minutes if you get up early. Best to plan your travel during non-commute hours.

Getting around is easy. Car services arrive so fast you have to be ready when you call. Buses run nearby that go nice places.

From here, head out to experience SF's world-class food, shopping, museums, parks, and other delights. If you're short on time, plan a meal in nearby Bernal Heights (10 mins by car), where you may get in without a reservation (but reservations recommended). Other di
host_about:
Your comfort is my first priority.  I provide quality furnishings and give you privacy.  I try to make sure you have everything you might need and am available to make recommendations about SF for you, or take care of any maintenance. 

My rentals are extremely well cleaned. The house is being extremely well ventilated, as it's on the top of a hill where it's breezy and sunny. We open every single closet, cabinet, and drawer and inspect them and let them ventilate.

All non-porous surfaces are cleaned with soap, ammonia, or bleach.  All fabric surfaces are either vacuumed or washed with a soapy cloth.  All linens and towels are washed with bleach in hot water.. 

The cleaners and I wear masks during cleaning. We use trash bags to avoid contact with trash and simplify cleaning the trash cans.  We try to run two loads of dishes between guests, so you may find a load running when you arrive. 

You can see the cleaning guidelines weÃ¢â¬â¢re following here:
 https://www.airbnb.com/resources/hosting-homes/a/cleaning-guidelines-to-help-prevent-the-spread-of-covid-19-163
  
I'll attempt to communicate with you in any language via Internet translation.

host_about:
I manage the house with Lita my 21 year old daughter & her father Fred. Having our house on Airbnb is helping us with our daughters college fund. She graduated from High School in 2019 & has taken a gap & COVID year before deciding on a university & country that she wants to go to school in. 

Renting our home also funded a new garden apartment that will be for a long term tenant.

Airbnb also helped fund 'Tartlet Bar',  a food business Wendy had with her families farm.

We own the house together, but split our time there with Lita our daughter. We co-parent & raised our daughter in whatÃ¢â¬â¢s called a Ã¢â¬ÅnestingÃ¢â¬Â situation. One of us are usually in town & available if you need anything.

We have lived in San Francisco since 1989, we get out of the city as much as possible, but always seem to return.

Wendy is a creative consultant & avid paddle boarder. She speaks French, English, understands Spanish & is learning Portuguese. She's currently a digital nomad making her way around the continents. One of her passions is to see the world and study different cultures, which she has done extensively (she wants to be an anthropologist when she grows up ;.). 

We believe the world is Lita's education, with 3 languages and several countries already under her belt she is a gypsy at heart. SheÃ¢â¬â¢s fluent in French, Spanish, English, & is teaching herself Japanese. She took 2019/2020 to explore Europe & work in Japan before she attends a University in 2022.

Fred is French, fluent in French, English & Spanish, a photographer, entrepreneur, surfer, world traveler and owns two small business in SF; Dalva (a bar in the mission district) and Grenouille-French Vintage Antiques.

We're also doing Airbnb because we like the idea of meeting like minded travelers, people who seek adventure, people who believe we can learn from everyone we meet and enjoy absorbing other cultures as much as we do. Is it possible to be part of a community while being a gypsy and a nomad? So far it's working out to be yes...

Located between Noe Valley and Castro, shops and restaurants are a pleasant walk down the hill on 24th, 18th, and Castro St. Street parking is easy to find, and major bus/subway stops are nearby.

The space
Your private bedroom and adjacent private bathroom are on the second floor, which has two other bedrooms. The third and top floor are where you will find the shared kitchen, living and dining room, patios, and access to the garden.

License number

We are at the center of everything! Stroll down the hill to the iconic and colorful Castro neighborhood, from which Downtown is a ~10 minute train ride, or take the F trolley for a historic San Francisco experience. The gourmet ghetto is within walking distance from us in the Mission District.

Enjoy morning coffee and pastries at: Tartine Bakery (if you do not mind the long line); Philz Coffee (try the Iced Mojito coffee); Le Marais (love the raisin bun); Neighbor's just two blocks from us (serving Andytown coffee; we love their matcha latte), to name a few.

Spoil your taste buds on all kinds of cuisines at awesome restaurants like: Pizza Delfina (not your average pizza place); Anchor Oyster Bar, Lark food & wine, Blush! wine bar, Takara sushi, Mama Ji's Chinese, etc. Way too many to list here.

neighborhood_overview:
My home is atop a very tall hill on Bridgeview Drive, aptly named, which real estate agents have called Ã¢â¬ÅSan FranciscoÃ¢â¬â¢s best kept secretÃ¢â¬Â because of the obvious bridge views, the warm sunbelt weather, easy, safe, free street parking, and the quick access to downtown San Francisco and the freeways to Silicon Valley. Bridgeview Drive is a unique winding hilltop street with a cozy, neighborly, super-safe atmosphere in a neighborhood called Silver Terrace. I have lived here for 17 years and have received only love and assistance from my dear neighbors of this family neighborhood.

host_about:
Hi there,
I am a healer, working with Hospice. I am inspired to drink life up, understanding that there is a finite amount of life to be had. I love to travel. My last amazing journey was to the Amazon. Even more memorable than the visual aspects of that trip were the auditory surprises. In addition to the contant vibrational buzzing and hissing in the air, I have 2 words for you, especially if you get to the Amazon: "Howler Monkeys". They truly sound like I imagine dinosaurs would sound. Apparently they get such volume and monster howl from a hole in a bone in their throats. Must be heard to be believed. But I digress! I'm a weekly dancer, pulling out the boots for two step, the retro wear for East Coast swing, and I waltz every chance I get no matter what I'm wearing. I love beautiful found objects. I write poetry and short stories. I have a private psychotherapy practice and teach mindfulness to people who are interested in more resiliency, more ZEST!  But I bet if you talked to my friends, they'd note the overall goofy, delighted way I like to carry on with life in general. As Helen Keller said, "Life is a banquet, but most of us are starving to death." So I invite you to come to my home and take a big bite out of life. The time is now.

host_about:
Your comfort is my first priority.  I provide quality furnishings and give you privacy.  I try to make sure you have everything you might need and am available to make recommendations about SF for you, or take care of any maintenance. 

My rentals are extremely well cleaned. The house is being extremely well ventilated, as it's on the top of a hill where it's breezy and sunny. We open every single closet, cabinet, and drawer and inspect them and let them ventilate.

All non-porous surfaces are cleaned with soap, ammonia, or bleach.  All fabric surfaces are either vacuumed or washed with a soapy cloth.  All linens and towels are washed with bleach in hot water.. 

The cleaners and I wear masks during cleaning. We use trash bags to avoid contact with trash and simplify cleaning the trash cans.  We try to run two loads of dishes between guests, so you may find a load running when you arrive.

neighborhood_overview: Bayview, just south of Islais Creek, is a community intent on reinventing itself as an artist's colony and gardening mecca. Both the Hunters Point Shipyard Artists Open Studio and Flora Grubb Gardens are cases in point. The neighborhood takes pride in its public and backyard gardens, and the San Francisco Produce Market provides local produce to many of San Francisco's finest restaurants. Three-quarters of the residents are loyal homeowners, many of whom have developed the Quesada Garden Initiative. This community-building effort started with a few neighbors beautifying Quesada Avenue and has blossomed into an award-winning project and serves as a model for communities across the nation. Properties are still affordable and comprised primarily of single-family residences. Architecture is a smorgasbord with some renovated projects, colorful stucco homes and Victorians.

host_about:
'Not all who wander are lost.' I love this quote. 
I am that wanderer, incredibly lucky to be infected with the passion and audacity to travel often and solo. 
I was born and raised in San Francisco. I am a native. I love my city. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve watched it evolve. But I have also left it many times in my youth. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left it to study abroad in France. Best decision of my college life! I backpacked solo around western Europe. 
IÃ¢â¬â¢ve left SF when I was in the military and stationed around our country. IÃ¢â¬â¢ve also driven as far north as Niagara Falls.
Career wise, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve spent over a decade in property management and rentals. I'm also a realtor. As a hobby, I write as often as possible, a pen and notebook on me at all times.

host_about: Hi!  We are Tim and Lisa.  These are a few of our favorite things: Our adopted city of San Francisco (we've both lived here over 3 decades), our local neighborhood (the Richmond District), meeting people, nature (birds/beaches/hiking/etc.), live music (especially at SF's fantastic music venues, including the music festivals right here in Golden Gate Park), food, and our family (we have 2 adult daughters and 2 grandkids).  We met while teaching at the well-respected preschool that Tim co-founded in 1984.  Tim comes from a hotel/restaurant family (The Treadway Inns in New England), and now newly retired, he looks forward to returning to his family roots as a friendly and helpful host.  Tim loves to garden and cook. Lisa still happily teaches 2-, 3- and 4-year-olds (coming up on her 31st year at the same school).  Like Tim, she is also from the East Coast (NY).  We put tons of love, care, comfort and quality into building our new apartment, as we expect to live down there ourselves one day.  We currently live upstairs from the apartment and are therefore easy to contact if you need anything (our guests choose how much or little interaction to have with us).  Please let us know if you have any questions!

host_about:
I run the high-end hospitality management company called Standout Stays.

I'm from South Africa and lived in Tokyo, Japan before moving to San Francisco over 25 years ago. I gave up my Business Development career in 2016 to focus full-time on short-term rentals. 

I have traveled to 50+ countries and stayed at some amazing places. I know what a difference great hospitality can make. I thus strive to create an experience at Standout Stays that will be memorable and unique. My aim is that you will come back and stay at our properties again each time you are back in the area.   

As a guest, I am responsible, trustworthy, and neat. Being a host myself, I can completely put myself in your shoes and am very respectful of your space. I love AirBNB because it affords one the opportunity to live like a local when you travel to a new area.  

I enjoy spending time with my dog (Dexter), working out, hiking, skiing, and generally making the most of life.   

If you are considering booking one of our listings, I know you will love your stay!  And for more information about our company, just search for us.

Hope to meet you soon,  
Laurence

neighborhood_overview:
Enchante Cafe is right next door. Bar Tradr Sam's is across the street...! Clement street is full of restaurants, bars and there is a movie theater. 38 bus comes right in front of the house and it takes you all the way to Downtown SF.

The Richmond District is a neighborhood in the northwest corner of San Francisco. It is bordered by Golden Gate Park on the south, the Pacific Ocean to the west, and Lincoln Park, Land's End, Mountain Lake Park, and the Presidio of San Francisco to the north, bisected by the Presidio Greenbelt. The Richmond has many influences from the Chinese-American culture. One of its three commercial strips, Clement Street in the Inner Richmond segment, is sometimes called the second Chinatown due to the high concentration of Chinese establishments. The other two commercial strips are Geary Boulevard and Balboa Street. The Richmond also has deep Irish and Russian roots and has many Catholic and Orthodox churches. neighborhood_overview:
Miraloma Park is a residential sanctuary with the vibe of San Francisco all around it. Bordered by seven other neighborhoods, its location offers residents a wide variety of activities in every direction.
Two of its largest surroundings are Glen Park and Diamond Heights to the east and Mt. Davidson (which occupies a large bubble of space within its borders). The homes here are built on curving streets, often into hills, lending them some of the most breathtaking views in San Francisco. And despite all of the noise and bustle of its surrounding neighbors and major thoroughfares, it remains a fairly serene environment anchored by a residential vibe.
Besides access to expansive outdoor green spaces, Miraloma Park is situated close to commercial hubs and public transportation lines. While there are a small number of shopping and dining opportunities along its borders, most residents travel further outside of the neighborhood limits for shopping essentials and bigger epicurean opt

neighborhood_overview:
Perfect if you have a car: street parking is extremely easy, no permit and no street cleaning schedules, which is so rare in San Francisco. It's a little away from the downtown area, but this also means that the neighborhood is safer, and it's really easy to go anywhere. Lots of local urban hikes to get some exercise and fresh air. People are very respectful of social distancing guidelines.
We're right by the 101, so going to SFO only takes 20 minutes, and you can get to the Embarcadero or the Golden Gate bridge very easily.
Cortland Avenue is right around the corner, it's the heart of Bernal Heights, with a wonderful grocery store (Good Life Grocery is the best) great restaurants, bars, boutiques, and my favorite place: Barebottle Brewing, they have an outdoor space and to go beer. It's either a 15 minutes walk (if you don't mind the hill), or a 5 minutes drive.
Checkout my local guidebook for recommendations!

host_about:
Born and raised in California, I have made San Francisco my home for 20 years and love it here so much that I saved up and finally bought a flat on one of my favorite Victorian, tree-lined streets in late 2012.

I lived in France for over 2 years and speak French fluently. I am a Francophile through and through. Travel is important to me and my family and I love having authentic local experiences that are unforgettable, which is why I love AirBnB. 

I'm very active. I run frequently to the beach through Golden Gate Park on up to Lands End, I hike often on Mt Tam, Mt Diablo and other nearby places, especially during spring wildflower season. I have enjoyed my many long backpacking trips in Yosemite, Kings Canyon and the Tetons.

neighborhood_overview:
Noe Valley is a quiet neighborhood, like a village within a city! It is kind of unique in having about the densest concentration of original Victorian homes dating from the 1850s until the 1900. The reason for the old Victorians (like mine!) is that Noe Valley was miraculously saved from the fire after the 1906 Earthquake because the fire hydrant at 20th and Church Streets was the first found with actual water pressure as the fire raced south from the city center. Earthquake. It served to preserve a firebreak at 20th St. Today you can see 20th century buildings on the North side of 20th and 19th century Victorians on the south side. And don't forget to check out the hydrant, lovingly painted gold.

Noe Valley is surrounded by interesting neighborhoods as well, including the historic and vibrant Latin cultural area called the Mission District as well as the Castro District, famous for it's role in the history of LGBTQ, celebrating many styles of living and loving that were

description:
Extraordinary location close to everything. 1.5 block to BART/Muni. This is Unit #4 in a 5-unit 1920's Edwardian building on a quiet street in SoMa, fully remodeled in 2018. It has an open kitchen/living area with eating bar. Each bedroom has a large closet & a work desk.
