The space
All new electrical, plumbing, insulation, walls, fixtures, etc. Sleek, quiet, efficient electric heating in each bedroom with separate thermostats. New and cool bathroom with tons of bathroom storage. New oak hardwood floors (no, not that Pergo sh*t you see all the time -- actual hardwood installed by an old Italian guy!). Washer/Dryer in the unit. All new cabinetry, granite kitchen. Dishwasher, garbage disposal. Plenty of hallway and bedroom closet sp
neighborhood_overview: One hundred year ago, SoMa (or South-of-Market) was built with wide boulevards that held warehouses or factories on the corners and the perimeter of each block. Nowadays, these are converted apartments or loft buildings.  The interior of the large blocks contained smaller street and were quiet "Residential Enclaves" of two- and three- story Edwardian flats, built with the last of the redwood from nearby forests in the 1910s and 20s. These enclaves today are hidden clusters of refurbished older homes that feel neighborly and almost private.  It's a highly walkable neighborhood with many bars, restaurants and clubs along the main roads, yet quiet and residential inside. Mid-SoMa, where we are, is very close to City Hall, a 1.5 block walk to Civic Center BART and Muni (which can get you anywhere in the region), easily walkable to Moscone Convention Center and the Financial and Hotel districts. Shopping at Union Square is about four blocks away!
host_about: I have lived in San Francisco for 30 years with a brief stint in Denver . My parents are in Asheville and it has become my second home over the last few years. I'm now here more than half-time. I am the co-founder the AIDS Memorial Quilt, which started on my back porch in 1987 (Younger people have no clue what this is, but a online search should help...) I've been running AIDS or LGBT organizations my whole adult life and enjoy the community-building aspect of what I do.  I recently retired as executive director of AIDS Emergency Fund and Breast Cancer Emergency Fund, two related non-profits that help low income people pay their basic living costs while disabled or going through surgery, chemo or radiation.  I am grateful to the many hosts on Airbnb who have opened their homes to me when I travel, and I was inspired by them top remodel this farmhouse for your enjoyment.

neighborhood_overview:
The Mission is on the sunny side of the city, away from the fog. 24th St is two blocks away and boasts an array of restaurants among the best in the cities. There is a BART station on 24th St that is walking distance. There are MUNI bus stops (and a bike line) right out front., offering a convenience access to downtown. There's a supermarket at 23rd and South Van Ness, and a Walgreens two blocks away.

The Mission is one of the most vibrant neighborhood in the city. It has become a trendy hotspot in the last decade due to its convenient location for commuters towards Silicon Valley and the peninsula (Palo Alto, Stanford). Indeed, there is an entrance to the 101/280 freeways a half mile away. But it has preserved its tradition and Hispanic heritage: you can still find the best Mexican food and view the colorful murals.

Stay in the guest suite in the basement of our 1912 craftsman home. Our family lives above, so you can hear us walking around, but we try to be considerate housemates. We live in the quiet Sunset/Parkside neighborhood one block from restaurants and transit. The suite does not have a kitchen, but there is a microwave, coffee maker, and mini fridge. The wifi is fast and there is a combo washer/dryer. FAQ: We're not near downtown or the tourist areas, but we are near buses to get you there.

The space
The guest suite has a private entrance, one bedroom with a queen bed, a bathroom with shower (no tub), a laundry room, coffee bar (no kitchen), and a living room with TV area and desk area.

Guest access
Enter the suite through the left side gate to the backyard and down the patio steps. There is a 2 hour parking zone on our street that is enforced 8am-6pm, but free 24 hour street parking is available 1-2 blocks south.

Other things t
neighborhood_overview:
Parkside neighborhood is quiet and residential, but has several interesting local restaurants a short walk away on Taraval St. For even more restaurants, the West Portal shopping / dining strip is a 15 minute walk east.

Our neighborhood is on the opposite end of the city from downtown and the tourist areas. It will take at least 30 minutes to get downtown, but driving can take up to an hour if it's rush hour. Transit takes 30-45 minutes depending on the time of day.
host_about: I have lived in San Francisco since 1999 and enjoy hiking, camping, and exploring new places. We have three boys in high school through college. My husband Scott is a bike rider and public transit enthusiast, so he can tell you the best way to get anywhere in The City. We'd love to meet you and welcome you to SF!

neighborhood_overview: San Francisco Marina District -The Marina District in named for its proximity to San Francisco's yacht harbors and the bay front walkway, but is known for its million dollar Mediterranean homes and its numerous restaurants and boutiques.The nearby Marina Green and Crissy Field are popular for jogging, windsurfing, and enjoying the spectacular views of the Golden Gate Bridge, Alcatraz and yachts sailing the Bay. Visit Chestnut Street for boutique shopping and alfresco dining.
host_about:
Built by the son of a California Gold Rush miner, the historic Marina Motel was built to celebrate the opening of the Golden Gate Bridge in the late 1930's and is still run by the same family. Ideally situated between Fisherman's Wharf and the Golden Gate Bridge in the popular Marina District, the Marina Motel offers a one-of-a-kind, old world experience. The first impression one has upon stepping into the motel's cobblestone courtyard is "Wow! This is like a little oasis back here with birds chirping, flowers EVERYWHERE, cute little garages and rooms decorated to feel like home. I feel like I'm in Europe."

Walk around the corner to the numerous outdoor cafes, restaurants and boutiques on Chestnut and Union Street, take a walk on the beach to the Golden Gate Bridge or rent a bike and ride across it while taking the ferry back, ride a cable car at Fisherman's Wharf or visit the de Young Museum or California Academy of Science in Golden Gate Park. The best of San Francisco is within easy reach.

neighborhood_overview: South of Market or "SoMa", San Francisco is rightfully named so for being just south of the famous Market Street. It has several sub-neighborhoods including Yerba Buena, Rincon Hill and South Beach, where the San Francisco Giants play waterfront baseball. SoMa is considered the cultural capital of the city, as it is home to many museums such as the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art (SFMOMA), the Yerba Buena Center for the Arts and the Contemporary Jewish Museum. The neighborhood is also a major business district, containing the Moscone Conference Center and numerous software and Internet company offices. Upscale shopping and dining establishments enhance this neighborhoodÃ¢â¬â¢s abundant appeal.

name: Private Room in Historic Haight Ashbury Victorian
description:
Private Bedroom with shared bath in San Francisco single family Victorian home. Centrally located in the Haight-Ashbury District of San Francisco, steps from the Golden Gate Park Panhandle, GG Park, & world famous Haight Street. Great walkability and easy public tranportation to major tourist areas of San Francisco.

The space
We offer a room in a single family home built in 1895. You chance to share life in an urban environment that offers lots of things to do in a relatively quiet setting.

Your room offers a Queen-size bed with new mattress. The room has been recently renovated, while still keeping its Victorian era charm. A quiet space overlooking our private deck. Despite renovations and updated systems, our home is 128 years old, and has been through 2 major earthquakes (1906 & 1989). The walls & corners may not be perfectly squared, and some doors stick when opening them, we call it Victorian charm.

You may note that our home is not ai
neighborhood_overview:
The Haight Ashbury was developed in the 1880s and 1890s, and many of the original buildings remain today from 'working class' Victorians such as our home to grand mansions that have been lovingly restored and maintained.

Free professionally led walking tours of the the historic Haight Ashbury are offered several Sundays each month.

This is a great walking area with shopping on Haight Street less than two blocks away. Golden Gate Park with its green expanses and Sunday carfree days, is minutes away, Both the de Young Museum, and the California Academy of Sciences in Golden Gate Park are an easy 20 minute walk away.

There are bike rental shops on Haight Street and along the borders of the GG Park. In addition the city sponsors a bike share program where one can rent a bike in one location, and drop it off in another location.
host_about:
John is American born (Dallas), but raised in the Washington DC area. Fell in love with California while attending graduate school at UCLA. After 3 years abroad - 1 year advanced studies in Bordeaux France and 2 years teaching at the University of the Witwatersrand in Johannesburg South Africa, he returned to California and has lived in San Francisco since 1974. He founded The Wine House, a wine import, wholesale, and retail business in San Francisco in 1977, which allowed him to combine his love of travel & interest in other cultures into a career centered on bringing people together through the pleasures of wine & food around the table. 

Renato has been in the travel and hospitality industry for many years. He arrived from Rio de Janeiro, and made his home in San Francisco since 1993. He continues to enjoy meeting and introducing guests to the many wonderful facets of our city.

Career wise, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve spent over a decade in property management and rentals. I'm also a realtor. As a hobby, I write as often as possible, a pen and notebook on me at all times.
I am cursed with this blessing of being unceasingly interested in people. I love meeting people. I love hearing stories. And I love writing them. 
As I review my lifeÃ¢â¬â¢s experiences, IÃ¢â¬â¢ve come upon one very simple realization, that proclaimed secret of success. It is merely this: Ã¢â¬ËSay what you will do and do what you will say.Ã¢â¬â¢

name: Spacious Unique Artist Built Sunny & Quiet 2BR Apt
description:
Large, light filled, quiet, private 2 bedroom apartment/guest suite with split bathroom (commode and sink in one room, bath/shower and sink in other), kitchenette, and ceilings up to 16'. We have been working on this space for the last 2 years to get the details just right, including hand built furniture and art by local artists. Above the din of the Mission, this apartment is a unique space built in the attic of a large Edwardian house run by artists Laurel Roth Hope and Andy Diaz Hope .

The space
This guest suite is a unique custom space perfect for a relaxing escape or productive work trip in San Francisco. No detail was spared--all of the doors and architectural details were loving restored from houses of the period of our building (the 1890's). Most of the furniture was custom built by us (Laurel and Andy) using the salvaged structural Douglas Fir removed during the construction process. I usually travel with my husband (who I sometimes collaborate with on artwork) and now our young daughter as well.

I'm pretty quiet and love animals, parks, reading, movies, and walking in new places.

Literally around the corner are restaurants and bars on Valencia street and grocery stores and more restaurants and bars on Mission street. You couldn't find a more central place to experience the trendy Mission yet you are in a peaceful setting. There is also a garden with a Meyer lemon tree, only in CA.

The space
Victorian on the outside, modern on the insight; bright and airy, high ceilings calm and comfortable furnished mid-century originals. The bedroom has bay windows facing West and gets lovely afternoon sun. The large living, dining and kitchen has a loft feeling and faces a small garden accessible through the back door.

neighborhood_overview:
The South of Market neighborhood (SOMA) is one of the longest standing and fastest growing areas of San Francisco. We are less than a mile from the bay and the beautiful Embarcadero boardwalk and bikeway, just two blocks from Moscone Center and Yerba Buena Gardens, and an easy walk to downtown shopping and Union square.

This is the heart of the city, which means there is a lot nearby. Transit, grocery stores, restaurants, excellent coffee shops, clubs, bars, museums, stadiums, and parks are all within an easy walk or bike. The Saturday morning farmer's market at the Ferry Building is wonderful, and the Civic Center farmer's market is also nearby on Sunday mornings and Wednesday afternoons.

We are also close to the Civic Center area and all that it has to offer, including the Symphony hall, the Opera House and ballet, and our gorgeous City Hall.

neighborhood_overview:
The Bayview has until recently, been the best-kept (and sunniest) secret of San Francisco. We are in the very southeast corner of the city, an area that is rapidly transforming with new residential developments.

All kinds of little gems are flourishing in our neighborhood as the rest of the city catches on to the great potential of this side of town. Flora Grubb Nursery and Cafe, San Francisco Mead Company, and Old School Cafe are a few local businesses I'd recommend checking out.

Our street has a tight-knit community of families who are very active in local affairs. There is a beehive in the community garden immediately opposite our house.

Powell Place is surrounded by everything that makes San Francisco special.

The space
The charm of Powell Place may entice you to spend your entire vacation inside your beautiful vacation home, but venture outside and you'll find access to all of San Francisco by boarding one of the city's cable cars, less than a half-block away.

name: Noe Valley/Dolores Heights Oasis, 30 Day Min.
description:
Amazing location on a quiet, family friendly block just minutes from two incredible neighborhoods, Noe Valley and the Mission. Both neighborhoods offer a plethora of great cafes, markets, shopping, the best restaurants, and nightlife right nearby. 10 minutes by foot from BART, a 12 minute walk to Whole Foods, and 15 minutes to the iconic Dolores Park. It's a quick and easy 10 minute BART ride to downtown, Union Square, and the Embarcardero.

The space
Two bedrooms, one bathroom, with the smaller bedroom doubling as a perfect work from home office. Large front patio with a picnic table, umbrella, and outdoor seating to relax and enjoy the sunny Mission/Noe weather. Smart TV and WiFi. The modern kitchen has stainless steel appliances as well a washer/dryer that you are welcome to use. There is an EcoBee thermostat with heating and fan. There is also ample closet space and storage in each of the bedrooms.

This is not a rental property, but my primary
neighborhood_overview: Beautiful, quiet street, with a lot of young families as neighbors.  Guerrero Market is a great little corner store for essentials, Chloe's cafe is a cute breakfast place a couple blocks away, and LoveJoy's Tea Room and Mr. Digby's are great spots for afternoon tea and happy hour.  Family friendly Noe Valley and the lively Mission District are both steps away, with plenty of markets, shopping, restaurants, and the best Mission taquerias, all within a 10 minute walk from the condo.
host_about: I've lived in San Francisco for the last 14 years and I'm currently renting my amazing condo in the Dolores Heights neighborhood, steps from Noe Valley and the Mission District.  I hope you enjoy my place as much as I do!

name: Stunning views from the Richmond Crows Nest
description:
Nestled in between Land End, Ocean Beach and Golden Gate Park, the apartment is the perfect space to explore from, and come back to recharge.

The neighbors refer to it as "The Crows Nest" because the apartment is set back from the road and feels very private. Yet with panoramic views, you feel like you're on top of the world and can see everything!

Fully stocked for a comfortable long term stay, this apartment is an excellent place to access a outdoor SF landmark experience.

The space
The house was built in the 1920 and the top floor apartment was added in the 1950's so it has delightful architectural details and incredible charm.

The kitchen has a restored gas Wedgewood from the 50's and the wood burning stove in the living room is from the same era. There is a new stackable washer and dryer in the hallway closet, so you can do laundry anytime. The sink basin in the bathroom is original but the faucet, toilet, shower and clawfo

I am an interior designer and am passionate about every aspect of the arts. I look at the bright side of life. Whether it means simply enjoying a great cup of coffee or listening to a good tune, I appreciate every moment life has to offer.  I have lived in SF for 15 years and consider it home.

name: Peaceful Mid-Century Modern 3 bd in San Francisco
description:
Inviting, lovingly cared for home, in safe and desirable Portola neighborhood of San Francisco.
The home itself is very clean with great mid century modern finishes, beautiful hardwood floors, upstairs deck off the main bedroom looks over our private yard. Enter through the classic San Francisco breezeway entrance to your spacious flat.
A few blocks away is McLaren Park, Jerry Garcia Amphiteatre and vibrant San Bruno ave.. Easy freeway/ SFO access, short bike/bus/ drive to the Civic center.

The space
The space is the upstairs area of our home which includes 3 bedrooms and 2 baths. The area is available as a private space for our guests.

Guest access
The entire upstairs suite is for guests as well as sharing our laundry area and breezeway. We ask not to use the yard because of our small pet dog that thinks he owns the place.
neighborhood_overview:
Safe and walkable neighborhood, blocks away from the second largest park in San Francisco. McLaren park boasts a huge public city golf course with amazing views, locals love the park because it's quiet and not run over by tourists. Downtown Portola sports a great little downtown street (San Bruno Ave) which is a short walk with great local and ethnic food spots, coffee shops and local flavor. One of the sunniest areas in fog city.

Grocery Outlet is a 15 min walk ( mostly flat), and SFO is 10 min's by car, with several city bus lines a block away.

host_about:
I live in a beautifully, newly decorated home by the Pacific Ocean.  I love the ocean.  The  fresh, crisp air that it brings rejuvenates me.  The ocean also reminds me of the far off lands I have visited, and the friends I have made when doing so.  Europe (Germany, Spain, Italy, Turkey), Mexico, Japan, Australia, New Zealand, and of course, where I am from, China, are just some of the places I have traveled.

I was a successful, award winning Cosmetologist in China, and moved to the United States to seek even greater opportunities. Today, I own several successful businesses, and help thousands of people achieve the beauty they desire.  However, what I really enjoy, is in sharing the richness of our cultural diversity with others...that is what makes America great. Our country has the ability to weave many diverse cultures  into a beautiful fabric that unifies all of us.  I truly look forward to sharing with others, and making their stay the most memorable experience possible.

neighborhood_overview:
YouÃ¢â¬â¢ll be right between Castro and Noe Valley and a short walk to the Mission District, some of the most vibrant and exciting neighborhoods in the city.

The Castro is one of the first predominantly gay neighborhoods in the nation and is a symbol for the LGBTQIA community. It continues to be a vibrant place with the famous Castro Theatre, GLBT History Museum, Rainbow Walk, and Pink Triangle Memorial Park.

Noe Valley is a charming neighborhood with boutique shopping, restaurants and cafes along the main drag of 24th street. It provides easy access to nearby Twin Peaks.

neighborhood_overview:
SOMA (South of Market) is the heart of San Francisco as its' business and entertainment district. Located in walking distance from BART, CalTrain, cafes, restaurants, clubs, grocery stores, Moscone Center, SF MOMA, Mission District, etc. Many tech and business professionals live here, as well as the crowd who likes to be in the center of everything.

My street is the quieter, tree-lined street in Soma, which allows you to have both - a restful stay and a stellar SF location. The convenience of SOMA does come with the proximity to SF downtown, which means that you may occasionally see homelessness in the streets. Please ask me about the best way to get around so I could advise you on the best route around the area.

Perfect for a quiet getaway in the heart of the city. Close to Glen Park canyon hiking trails and just minutes from all that San Francisco has to offer. Remodeled with modern amenities. Features an atrium and open floor plan with floor-to-ceiling window. The house backs to open space for ultimate privacy.

The space
An architect-designed house with a mid-century bar, dedicated kids room and beautiful outdoor space. Parents and kids alike will love the large yard and deck, outdoor jacuzzi spa, cozy fireplaces and the bbq for al fresco family meals. There is a large office for those looking to work from home, but when youÃ¢â¬â¢re ready to log off and unplug, it backs on to open space for ultimate privacy and a peaceful, serene outlook.

This residence has 3 bedrooms and 3 bathrooms, all bedrooms on the same fl
neighborhood_overview:
Towering above Noe Valley on the north and Glen Canyon to the south, the neighborhood of Diamond Heights offers some of the best views in the city. Developed in the 1960s, this is a quiet, peaceful residential district tucked along the streets that wind beneath eucalyptus. Charming, tree canopied stairway walks connect the streets, and provide steep short cuts and breathtaking views.

The neighborhood has the laid back feel of a suburb within the city limits. Home to approximately 100 prized Eichlers built on seven distinct floor plans, Diamond Heights is an undiscovered gem.

It's centrally located to much of what the city has on offer. Noe Valley is a 15-minute walk, and downtown San Francisco a short 10 minute drive. The Mission is just a 5 minute drive away.

Plentiful street parking in the neighborhood.
host_about: We are Geoff and Tati, a San Francisco based couple. Our Diamond Heights home embodies our passion for mid century design and we look forward to sharing it with you.

Nearby,   Duboce Park has a playground and popular off-leash dog area.

name: Modern + Spacious 1BR/1BA Merced Manor Apartment
description:
Enjoy the city life by day and come home to a spacious, modern and clean 1BD/1BA with a full kitchen and separate side entrance located in a safe and quiet neighborhood with ample street parking. The apartment is within walking distance to modern conveniences (restaurants, grocery stores, Stonestown Galleria), nearby the great outdoors (lake, park, golf course, SF Zoo), and near direct public transport lines to the Financial District/Union Square and Golden Gate Park/Golden Gate Bridge.

The space
Enter the Merced Manor Apartment in your private side entrance with a keyless PIN code (or app, your preference) so you can self check-in at your leisure.

The kitchen is stocked with utensils and cookware for those that like to stay in to eat and has a mini-fridge with a small freezer unit for any groceries. Additionally, there is a fully stocked tea + coffee station available for your morning caffeine fix.

The bathroom has a large walk-in shower
neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood feels like a world away from the hustle and bustle of city life - it is quiet and safe, with easy street parking - yet is within walking distance to a major mall with restaurants (Stonestown Galleria), two grocery stores (Trader JoeÃ¢â¬â¢s and Whole Foods), a movie theater, and a big box discount store (Target).  The apartment is also located by San Francisco State University, the historic Harding Park golf course, and is walking distance to a small playground (half-block away) and Lake Merced.  There is also a local farmers market about a 2 min walk away that takes place on Sundays from 9am-1pm.
host_about: San Francisco born and raised, friendly, social and responsible person who likes to travel and explore the way locals live everyday.  I love learning about different cultures and being able to show people the city I love.

neighborhood_overview:
One of San FranciscoÃ¢â¬â¢s oldest and authentically diverse communities. Bayview-Hunters Point history includes the indigenous Muwekma Ohlone tribes, with documented history dating to 2000 B.C; and with later contact between early Spanish explorers and native dwellers along the shores of Islais Creek, one of seven major watersheds in the Southeast part of San Francisco.

Some people are put off by the area and claim that it 'appears' to be dangerous and sketchy. We find these comments to be uninformed and reactionary. San Francisco is an urban and dense City. WeÃ¢â¬â¢ve lived here in Bayview for over 40 (forty years) and enjoy and respect this community as our home. We trust that you will feel the same during your visit. WELCOME !

name: Enjoy SF Like a Local
description: This sleek San Francisco flat is the perfect work retreat: blocks from BART, muni, and highways 280 and 101 in downtown Glen Park. With ample space to spread out, fiber internet, and modern decor, this apartment embodies modern San Francisco in a very traditional Victorian flat. When you are done with work for the day-- go hiking in Glen Park canyon or for drinks in the Mission, Noe Valley, or Bernal Heights, all within walking distance.
neighborhood_overview:
Glen Park is a quiet, residential area know for a sweet downtown village and convenient access to everywhere else.

Glen Park Village has all the necessities you will need for your stay: a few restaurants, an upscale market, and a several boutiques within blocks. The commercial areas of Bernal Heights, Noe Valley, and the Mission are all within a mile. A few minutes away, Glen Park Canyon and McLaren Park let you forget you are in a big city as you explore the trails, rock climbing, tennis courts, picnic spots, and vistas.

BART, muni, highways 101 and 280, and a rack of city bikes are all within a few blocks. Glen Park is a great starting point for commutes to downtown, the East Bay, or the Peninsula/Silicon Valley.

neighborhood_overview:
Noe Valley feels like a small town despite its centrality in San Francisco. As the name suggests, it's bordered by hills, giving it an intimate feel. 24th Street is the main drag and the Bungalow is 4 blocks away. You will discover great restaurants, indie coffee roasters, juice bars, yoga studios and boutique shopping. Farmers Market is every Saturday morning in the Town Square.

6 blocks north and you are in the Castro! You'll find the Castro Theatre, a historic SF landmark, lively bars, lots of outside dining, a vibrant community & lots of photo worthy murals.

You can also walk to Dolores Park, one of SFÃ¢â¬â¢s most popular parks & the Mission, ground zero for hipness.

Public transportation from Noe and the Castro is a breeze and I'm happy to help.

Noe Valley and the Castro have some of the best weather in the city.

description:
Perfect for families and friends. Located on top of Potrero Hill one of the best neighborhoods to have a magnificent view of the city. Spacious house with a terrace and garden. Fast Wifi, free parking, access to Netflix, Amazon. Very close to downtown, the Mission, Castro, Ferry building, AT&T Giants, Chase Center, general hospital, UCSF, just 15 minutes from the airport. Great restaurants, wineries, parks and the historic Anchor Steam brewery in the neighborhood.

The space
Cozy living room with fire place and books. Enjoy a glass of wine, or a cup of coffee in the terrace filled with beautiful sunsets watching the cargo ships coming from the Pacific Ocean crossing under the Bay Bridge with views of Oakland, Berkeley hills, downtown SF. Then turn the lights on and enjoy the magic vibes in the garden.

Guest access

In the main floor, guests can access to the living room, dining room, two bedrooms, one bathroom,
neighborhood_overview: Potrero Hill is a neighborhood with a perfect SF vibe. It is residential and yet very close to the main attractions in the city. McKinley Park is a block from the house with great views and a big playground for the kids. Next to the park a beautiful community garden where the sunsets are breathtaking. Around the corner Chiotras a very convenient Grocery Store. A cozy deli known for its sandwiches. Enjoy breakfast in Plow one of the most famous places in SF to have brunch. Before dinner enjoy a glass of wine at Ruby an organic natural winery then pick from a verity of restaurants around. French, Mexican, American, Japanese, Peruvian etc. Goat hill pizza is a traditional sf spot since 1975 making the best sourdough pies in the city. Thinkers Cafe opens early and is just a few blocks away. Have a tour at the historic Anchor Brewing Company stablished since 1896 followed by a tasting session.

I have a very close connection with friends and family. I adore animals and nature.
I'm very respectful, honest, tolerant and kind with others.

name: Neat room 4, dorm-style stay in historic victorian
description:
Enjoy a bright and updated stay in this historic victorian building! Located in the southeast section of San Francisco, this private room is perfect for 1-2 travelers who are in San Francisco for work or to see the sites. The bed has a trundle with a twinXL for a 2nd guest. The T-train (public transportation) is accessible from your doorstep and is just 6 stops to UCSF and Chase Center. Free street parking is available. Overnight parking in a gated lot available for a fee.

The space
The room measures 8'8'' x 11'9'' plus a closet that is 3' x 5'8''. The room is located on the 2nd floor above a bakery. The 2nd floor has a total of 6 bedrooms (2 for permanent residents and 4 for guests) as well as a non-profit office space. Your room has key code access, so it is only accessible to you during your stay.

There is a full, shared kitchen with a stove and oven, microwave, and refrigerator. There are 2 shower rooms and 2 toilet rooms. Though they are shared, t
neighborhood_overview: India Basin is a historic neighborhood in southeast San Francisco. It's a diverse neighborhood, and you will likely come across people from many different walks of life. The building is located on 3rd Street, which is full of small businesses, restaurants, and corner stores. Within a 3-block radius, our part of 3rd Street has a number of "mom-and-pop" restaurants (including a couple of sandwich shops, a pizza place, a Chinese restaurant, a dive bar, and a taqueria) as well as Starbucks and Subway. If you are looking for trendier eats, you can hop on the T-train right in front of the house and take it 3 stops to the heart of the popular Dogpatch or take it further down to Mission Bay or The Embarcadero.

name: Full-floor Penthouse | Ocean View, Parking(2br1ba)
description:
This full-floor Penthouse Suite is on the top floor of a 4-level single family house on Ashbury Heights (whole house has been listed since 2017 with 100+ all five-star reviews: https://www.airbnb.com/h/ashburytommy).

The suite has 1 large bedroom w/ a queen bed, a study w/ a twin XL bed, and a bathroom. Equipped w/ all new amenities, 75" Sony UHD TV w/ stereo, adjustable height desk, mini-fridge, home safe.

Perfect for a traveling executive, a couple (+1 kid) or two co-workers/friends!

The space
The Penthouse Suite is part of a single family house, not a separate apartment. You enter from the main entrance of the house and go through the staircase to the third/top floor. The Penthouse Suite occupies the entire top floor, with nearly 1,000 sq indoor/outdoor space. I live in the house, which is my primary residence, and work in downtown San Francisco. You will not see me much but IÃ¢â¬â¢m always just a text or phone call away! Free parking o
neighborhood_overview: Ashbury Heights is a centrally located upscale residential neighborhood (literally San Francisco's geographic center). High up on the hills, surrounded by parks and beautiful lush greenery, and walking distance to commercial streets in nearby Cole Valley and Haight Ashbury Historic District, as well as Golden Gate Park, Buena Vista Park, Tank Hill and Twin Peaks.  An easy 15-20 minute Muni train/bus or Uber/Lyft ride to downtown San Francisco, Union Square and Financial District.
host_about: I'm a finance professional working in downtown San Francisco. Outside of work, I love languages, opera, classical music and the great outdoors. Do not get to travel the world as much as I like due to busy work schedules but still manage to get away every once in a while to explore different cultures and to relax. My recent get-always include a week in Brazil, a week in Central Europe, a weekend trip in Bangkok and a long weekend in Boracay, the Philippines! Never thought I would host on airbnb, but why not have the world come to you when you cannot travel all corners of the world?! If you appreciate finer things in life, traditional elegance with modern touches, having your space immaculate with no clutter, you will enjoy staying at my house!

neighborhood_overview:
NOPA, San Francisco - What Is In A Name?
Thought all of the city's great neighborhoods were downtown? Think again. Welcome to NOPA (North of the Panhandle) - one of the city's most diverse and interesting areas. Recently rediscovered by San Franciscans, NOPA is on the cusp of the better-known Haight-Ashbury district. Beautifully situated on top of Golden Gate Park's panhandle. It boasts some of the best dining and entertainment in the city, and its residential, slightly quieter feel makes it very attractive as a respite from the bustle of the Financial District or SOMA.

NOPA boasts a number of great nightclubs and tasty restaurants: The Independent and Madrone are particularly popular with the club set, and Little Star Pizza, is routinely praised by Chicagoans as the best Pizza west of The Second City.

neighborhood_overview:
Pacific Heights San Francisco is a truly beautiful and classic SF neighborhood. It embodies the city you see in the movies with historic and colorful Victorians and mansions. It's also a fun district to go shopping in with locally owned shops as well as internationally recognized high-end brands.

Other fun things to do here include climbing the Lyon Street Steps, soaking in the views of the Bay and checking out the outside of the Mrs. Doubtfire house. You can also enjoy its restaurants, bars, and coffee shops.

It is one of the few areas in San Francisco that survived the 1906 earthquake and fire. This is why you can still find old, colorful Victorian homes from the late 1800s. This upscale neighborhood also has gorgeous mansions lining several of its famous streets.

Sunnyside is a quiet, family-oriented neighborhood located just south of Twin Peaks. Peaceful in the early mornings and at night.

1. Enjoy walking or biking in the hills that occupy nearby Westwood, Monterey Heights, and St. Francis Woods.
2. Eat or shop at nearby West Portal, Ocean Avenue, or Glen Park.
3. A Safeway is open late is located on the same block.
4. Whole Foods is a 3 minute drive away.
5. A pizza parlor is on the corner.
6. Railroad Espresso is two blocks away.
7. A string of restaurants line adjacent Monterey Boulevard.
8. Stonestown Galleria, a major mall, is a 10 minute drive away.
9. A playground is a block away, Sunnyside Playground is 3 blocks away, and Sunnyside Conservatory is a 8 minute walk.

neighborhood_overview:

Walk to work to FiDi, stroll to dimsum and the best spicy Chinese food in SF, or enjoy excellent Italian seafood in the heart of North Beach. Walking distance to transit for work, or a ride on the cable car.

We're wind-protected and on the sunny side of SF's fog belt. Always a plus in SF!

Anyplace creates spaces that are designed for productivity, catered to remote workers, digital nomads, corporate travelers, and students. All of our apartments and studios come prepped with a fully equipped home office, unlike anything found in other rentals.

neighborhood_overview:
5 min away from the modern hub of San Francisco's vibrant Mission District, Valencia Street is home to some of the city's hottest destination eateries, funky independent shops, the most crowded watering holes, and eye-popping murals.
15 min walk from Mission Dolores: At the corner of 16th and Dolores streets, overshadowed by an ornate basilica, sits a modest adobe chapel, one of the two original missions in San Francisco and the oldest standing building in the city. The inside of the chapel (note the ceiling patterned after Costonoan basket weaving -- Costonoans were the native inhabitants of the area) and the mission's cemetery and gardens will give you a feel for old times.

Stroll along the Mission's wide avenues and you'll be struck by the profusion of taquerias, pupuserias, produce markets, Salvadoran bakeries, salon de bellezas (beauty salons), auto-repair shops and check-cashing centers that post rates for wiring money to Guatemala and Nicaragua -- all evidence o
host_about:
My name is Ari.
I'm an avid learner and a bookworm, love reading about bio-hacking, economic trends, and ecology. I'm active in a few environmental orgs to promote bio-diversity (saving our planet is so important.. and happy to share advice).
I love kite surfing and play piano as well. Would be a pleasure to host anyone and answer any questions so you can have a perfect stay. 
Always strive to improve and provide everything you need for a perfect stay: instant booking,  24/7 response, fully equipped room with all the needed essentials to make your stay pleasant.

5 min away from the modern hub of San Francisco's vibrant Mission District, Valencia Street is home to some of the city's hottest destination eateries, funky independent shops, the most crowded watering holes, and eye-popping murals.
Live your best SF life in this Mission District neighborhood that's close to Dolores Park. This spot is a true walker's paradise with a 100 Walk Score. Named for Mission Dolores founded in 1776, San Francisco's oldest neighborhood has some of its hottest new restaurants and galleries. Boasting some of the best weather in the city, the Mission District, Bernal Heights and Potrero Hill take advantage of an abundance of fog-free days. New restaurants and night spots are a draw while Mission Dolores, 16th and Dolores streets, is the oldest structure in San Francisco. The largest concentration of murals in the city adorn buildings, fences and walls throughout the district.

5 min away from the modern hub of San Francisco's vibrant Mission District, Valencia Street is home to some of the city's hottest destination eateries, funky independent shops, the most crowded watering holes, and eye-popping murals.
15 min walk from Mission Dolores: At the corner of 16th and Dolores streets, overshadowed by an ornate basilica, sits a modest adobe chapel, one of the two original missions in San Francisco and the oldest standing building in the city. The inside of the chapel (note the ceiling patterned after Costonoan basket weaving -- Costonoans were the native inhabitants of the area) and the mission's cemetery and gardens will give you a feel for old times.

This charming renovated studio / one bath feels like an inviting English cottage in the middle of San Francisco. Located only a 10-min walk to Bart (SF's subway system) and an easy stroll to parks and restaurants, the space also features a private entry, outdoor patio, and in-unit laundry.

The space
30-day minimum stay required.

The space is located above Glen Park Village, the neighborhood's commercial core where you can find boutique shops, restaurants, and a small locally-owned grocery store that makes some of the best sandwiches in San Francisco. Neighbors with the Mission, Bernal Heights, and Noe Valley, you'll find plenty of fantastic architecture, hip shops, and places to see nearby.

Nestled on a hill, this southern-facing unit provides wonderful lighting and is fully-equipped with:

- a separate private entrance
- a private patio overlooking a beautiful backyard & trees
- fully stocked kitchen with cooking uten
neighborhood_overview: Glen Park is centrally located with convenient access to freeways, the subway, and bus systems. Neighbored by the Mission, Bernal Heights, and Noe Valley, you'll also find plenty of amenities in Glen Park. Glen Park Village offers restaurants, coffee shops, and small local stores. The 70-acre Glen Canyon Park has a playground, a recreation center with rock climbing, tennis courts, and hiking trails. Hike from the park to Twin Peaks for some breathtaking views!

neighborhood_overview:
Civic Center is distinguished by its many beaux arts-style government buildings and performing arts venues. City Hall, a sprawling 1915 landmark with a gold-leafed dome, anchors a complex that includes the elegant War Memorial Opera House, the Asian Art Museum and a large plaza. Entertainment seekers choose from plays at historic theaters, and concerts at sleek spots such as Davis Symphony Hall and the SFJazz Center.

Within 2 blocks to the west is Hayes Valley, a cool, revitalized neighborhood in the Western Addition. The main commercial stretch, Hayes Street, teems with upscale boutiques for designer fashions and home decor, plus dessert shops, chill watering holes and a wide array of on-trend restaurants.

neighborhood_overview: Surrounded on 3 sides by parkland and the ocean, the very quiet, safe and peaceful Richmond District borders Golden Gate Park to the south, the Presidio park to the north, and Ocean Beach to the west. neighborhood_overview:
Russian Hill is directly to the north (and slightly downhill) from Nob Hill, to the south (uphill) from Fisherman's Wharf, and to the west of the North Beach neighborhood. The Hill is bordered on its west side by parts of the neighborhoods of Cow Hollow and the Marina District.

At the northern foot of the hill is Ghirardelli Square, which sits on the waterfront of the San Francisco Bay, Aquatic Park, and Fisherman's Wharf, a popular tourist area. A trip down the winding turns of Lombard Street and across Columbus Avenue to the east leads to the neighborhood of North Beach. Down the hill to the west, past Van Ness Avenue, are Cow Hollow and the Marina districts.

name: Bright home in Castro/Mission
description:
Visit San Francisco like a local from our bright, stylish, central apartment.

Our apartment is a block from Muni Church Station, from multiple Bay Wheels bikeshare stations, and very close to attractions like the Castro, Dolores Park, and Valencia Street.

It's outfitted with a full chef's kitchen (gas + induction stoves), a beautiful, plant-filled dining room, and a cozy, relaxing living room with projector setup.

We look forward to answering your questions and welcoming you to the city!

License number

neighborhood_overview:
Market Street, with its streetcars and transit access, is just north; beyond that to the north is the bougie Hayes Valley neighborhood, Duboce Triangle with its dog park and the "the wiggle" bike route to Golden Gate Park, and famous/pretty Alamo Square and the Painted Ladies.

3 blocks south is Dolores Park, with stunning views, a dog-friendly area, and lots of people-watching.

2 blocks east is Valencia street, with bougie shops and lots of bars and restaurants. I would avoid Mission St and Van Ness St and that part of the Mission; it can be sketchy -- to explore the neighborhood's Latin heritage, I'd recommend hanging out on 24th St, near Folsom St.

West/southwest is the vibrant Castro neighborhood, among the first LGBTQ+ neighborhoods in the country. There are lots of gay bars, clubs, and gay-friendly businesses, as well as great restaurants.

Hi! I'm Lawrence, a native of San Francisco, born and raised in the Richmond district. I have deep roots in this city. My father was born here and my mother immigrated here at a very young age. My entire extended family have all stayed local to San Francisco. This city is more than just a magical place, it's who I am. 

As a host: I want everyone to feel like my home is theirs. This is my sanctuary, where I unwind after a long day or spend quality time with family and friends. I hope you love this neighborhood and all that it has to offer as much as I do, from cute mom-and-pop shops to delicious restaurants. I want to make your stay enjoyable, comfortable, and relaxing. Traveling should be fun and easy. Your accommodations should be too!

As a guest, I love exploring new countries and cities. Hotels are nice but staying in local homes is a great way to experience true local living. I enjoy an awesome food scene, stunning architecture, rich colors and textures, and most of all, warm and inviting people. 

I enjoy cooking and eating, working out, yoga, running, tennis, real estate, interior design, and of course, traveling!

description:
Our completely renovated, modern condo, has spectacular views of the bay. We are a 15 minute walk to the Chase Center and about 1 mile from Oracle Park. Our condo is in a quiet residential neighborhood, but a short walk to the main dinning areas of Potrero Hill and Dogpatch; and a quick uber ride to the Mission District, Hayes Valley and Fisherman's Wharf. The main living area is a combo living/dinning/kitchen open space with beautiful views of the San Francisco bay. It's a great spot to watch

name: Urban oasis!  Deck, city views, entire place
description:
Welcome to San Francisco! Looking for the perfect place to stay while visiting the city? Look no further than this charming and contemporary studio that offers panoramic views of the city's skyline and a glimpse of the iconic GG Bridge from your private deck.
Located just a short walk from Mission, you'll be able to explore the city easily. Whether you're in town for business or pleasure, this urban paradise will make you feel right at home. A bonus - easy street parking! Book your stay today!

The space
Our cozy suite has all the amenities to make your stay comfortable, including strong Wi-Fi, a flat-screen TV, and a fully equipped kitchen. The place comes with a luxurious king bed, plus a sleeper sofa for additional sleeping space.
Are you a coffee lover looking for the perfect way to start your day? Our coffee bar is fitted with a few coffee styles: a Drip maker, Nespresso machine, French press, Aeropress, and even cezve to make your ideal cup of co
neighborhood_overview:
Peralta Heights is a hidden urban oasis on the sunny north slope of Bernal Heights - one of SF's lesser-known best neighborhoods! This neighborhood offers residents an urban-suburban mix feel; there are a lot of bars, restaurants, coffee shops, and parks, but also lots of urban trail hikes and serene gardens with stunning views over the city.
Many of the Peralta Heights residences are relatively historic, built no later than 1939 and quite a bit earlier in some cases. You'll find a mix of old-timers living here for a few decades, with more recently moving young professionals appreciating the diversity of this location.
Peralta Heights has excellent public transportation and is very bikeable.

Nearby neighborhoods: Bernal Heights, Mission District, Potrero Hill, Holly Park, and Dolores Heights.

neighborhood_overview:
We are just two blocks from Golden Gate Park. This iconic park is home to a variety of recreational activities including a popular disc golf course, archery, walking/running/biking paths, roller skating dance parties, beautiful street art, a bison paddock, and more! Also nearby is the beach, where you can enjoy the fresh ocean air and beautiful views. Finally, we have the Presidio Golf Course nearby as well.

The Richmond District is also home to several world-class museums, including the DeYoung Museum, the Academy of Science (which has a fun nightlife event on Thursday nights), and the Legion of Honor.

neighborhood_overview:
Outer Richmond is a mellow beach town that can feel worlds away from the bustling neighborhoods to the east. The district spans the western edge of the city and is sandwiched between the Presidio (national park land) to the north, Golden Gate Park to the south and with 19th Avenue acting as the arbitrary cutoff point to the East.

Previously an empty tract full of sand that ran into the ocean, the Richmond has been growing steadily for the last 100 years. It features numerous grand attractions near its edges, including China Beach, Baker Beach, the ruins of the Sutro Baths, LandsÃ¢â¬â¢ End, Sea Cliff, and the Legion of Honor.

Outer Richmond is an area that many San Francisco residents and tourists donÃ¢â¬â¢t take the time to really explore (mostly because there is so much more going on in the eastern parts of the city). But those who have visited often express their wish to hang out there more.

Unassuming ethnic restaurants can be found all over and nightlife ten

Russian Hill is directly to the north (and slightly downhill) from Nob Hill, to the south (uphill) from Fisherman's Wharf, and to the west of the North Beach neighborhood. The Hill is bordered on its west side by parts of the neighborhoods of Cow Hollow and the Marina District.

Down the hill to the west, past Van Ness Avenue, are Cow Hollow and the Marina districts.

neighborhood_overview:
Located in the Outer Mission area in San Francisco. It is ethnically diverse and is bustling with families. Staying in a local neighborhood is less expensive and yet youÃ¢â¬â¢re just minutes away from the trendy areas of San Francisco. The place is just ÃÂ½ mile to freeway access to South San Francisco, Daly City and the peninsular and the East Bay.

There are colorful murals around the neighborhoods. Casual Mexican and Asian food spots dot the streets, along with diners, corner stores, and ethnic markets.

Outer Mission borders Excelsior District which is home to the Excelsior Festival, an annual event celebrating its cultural diversity. It brings in about 5,000 people each year and has free music and entertainment. There is also Jerry Day, a celebration of the areaÃ¢â¬â¢s most famous former resident, Jerry Garcia, lead singer of the Grateful Dead.

neighborhood_overview:
The historic neighborhood features many sights. Just 5 minutes walk from our home, you'll find Dolores Park which is featured in many films because of it's spectacular views, including: "Just Like Heaven," "Casualties of War," "Sweet November" with Charlize Theron, "Dirty Harry," The Layover," "Class Action," to name a few.
The Mission Dolores is 1 1/2 blocks away, & is a very interesting place to explore.
Castro Street features historical plaques about notable citizens & is the home the beautifully restored Castro Theater, featured in the movie "Milk" starring Sean Penn & James Franco.
10 minutes walk you'll find Valencia Street, home of the Mission-style burrito, plus many any other restaurants. 20 minutes the other way, you'll find the Haight Ashbury Neighborhood.
If you like sports, the Chase Center & ATT Park are easy to get to by MUNI subway which you can catch by walking 5-10 minutes to Church & Market Streets. If you work in one of the hospitals--most are v
host_about:
I've lived in San Francisco all my life and love giving visitors tips about our hidden gems and fun things to do here.  If you already know the ropes--no problem, but if you'd like some ideas about places to check out & things to do, don't hesitate to ask.
The Castro where you will be staying is my favorite neighborhood. We're friendly, have fantastic restaurants & cool places like the historic Castro Theater Movie Palace & Dolores Park just a short walk away.
I'm a non-smoker, pretty easy-going. I got into Air B&B because I enjoyed the experiences I've had traveling and wanted to open up my home to fellow travelers. The "City," as it's known here, is probably the most European city in the U.S. and that may be why folks from Europe tend to feel at home here (please don't call it "SAN FRAN" or "Frisco! ;))). San Francisco is internationally known for its gorgeous views and unique architectural beauty, excellent restaurants for any price-range, and of course, our free-spirited philosophy.  It gives me a lot of happiness to share this experience with you.

neighborhood_overview:
Russian Hill is directly to the north (and slightly downhill) from Nob Hill, to the south (uphill) from Fisherman's Wharf, and to the west of the North Beach neighborhood. The Hill is bordered on its west side by parts of the neighborhoods of Cow Hollow and the Marina District.

At the northern foot of the hill is Ghirardelli Square, which sits on the waterfront of the San Francisco Bay, Aquatic Park, and Fisherman's Wharf, a popular tourist area. A trip down the winding turns of Lombard Street and across Columbus Avenue to the east leads to the neighborhood of North Beach. Down the hill to the west, past Van Ness Avenue, are Cow Hollow and the Marina districts.

description:
Welcome to Urban Oasis, our newly renovated and beautifully designed apartment in the desirable neighborhood of Laurel Heights in San Francisco. Our space offers a perfect blend of city living and serenity, providing guests with a peaceful retreat in the heart of the city.

The space
This master suite is fully renovated with a private entry and a private backyard space. The suite is in the backside of the house, facing the backyard, on the bottom floor.

We offer brand-new furniture and appliances, with a spacious living room and bedroom - perfect for relaxing after a long day exploring the city. We also offer a walk-in closet with ample storage space.

The suite is spacious enough to fit up to four comfortably, with a queen bed in the master bedroom and a sofa bed in the living room.

You will also have access to your private backyard, where guests can take in the sun and enjoy the fresh air.

The kitchen has a full fridge
neighborhood_overview:
Laurel Heights is a posh neighborhood in San Francisco, located south of Pacific Heights and west of Presidio Heights. It offers tree-lined streets, Victorian-style homes, parks, and playgrounds. The neighborhood is considered one of the more upscale areas of San Francisco, and has easy access to all parts of the city.

Our location is unbeatable, with easy access to public transportation and many of the city's top attractions. The house is just minutes away from the iconic Golden Gate Park, and the vibrant neighborhoods of Presidio, Pacific Heights, and Presidio Heights. Also, we are a short drive away from the Golden Gate Bridge, and Alcatraz Island.

If you're here for an extended stay, we're a 30-minute commute to anywhere in downtown SF (SOMA, Union Sq). Also just minutes away from Trader Joe's or the Richmond neighborhood for delicious Asian food.

neighborhood_overview:
Russian Hill is directly to the north (and slightly downhill) from Nob Hill, to the south (uphill) from Fisherman's Wharf, and to the west of the North Beach neighborhood. The Hill is bordered on its west side by parts of the neighborhoods of Cow Hollow and the Marina District.

At the northern foot of the hill is Ghirardelli Square, which sits on the waterfront of the San Francisco Bay, Aquatic Park, and Fisherman's Wharf, a popular tourist area. A trip down the winding turns of Lombard Street and across Columbus Avenue to the east leads to the neighborhood of North Beach. Down the hill to the west, past Van Ness Avenue, are Cow Hollow and the Marina districts.
